{[%evp 0,6,19,31,19,-16,-3,-3,19]} 1. d4 {A warm welcome to the final part—the last course in the "1.d4 According to Dreev" series. In this section, we’ll cover all the most important sidelines that Black can play against 1.d4.} d5 (1... Nf6 2. c4 b6 {The Accelerated Queen’s Indian is quite popular nowadays, and we will examine it in detail in Chapter 7.} (2... Nc6 $5 {There’s still some debate over whether this line should be called the “Tango” or the “Mexican Defense.” Either way, we’ll cover it in Chapter 5.}) (2... e5 {The Budapest Gambit will be analyzed in Chapter 6.}) (2... d6 {The Old Indian will be covered in Chapter 8.}) ({In Chapter 9, we will discuss a modern and tricky line in the King’s Indian, arising after the moves} 2... g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3 Bd7 $5 {[%csl Bd7]} 7. O-O Re8 {An interesting line that has been tried by young and strong Grandmasters such as Van Foreest, Dubov, Maghsoodloo, and many others. We will take a closer look at it in Chapter 9.})) (1... f5 {The final part of this database will be dedicated to the Dutch Defense.} 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 (3... g6 {The Leningrad will be analyzed in Chapter 13, and here our recommendation will be to go for the mainline} 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 {Now Black's most important moves are c6, Nc6, Qe8 and e6.}) 4. Nf3 d5 (4... Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 {The Classical Dutch will be analyzed in Chapter 14.}) 5. c4 c6 {The Stonewall will be analyzed in the last Chapter 15.}) 2. c4 e6 (2... Bf5 {The Baltic defense and other sidelines will be discussed in Chapter 4.}) (2... e5 {The Albin Gambit will be analyzed in Chapter 1.}) (2... Nc6 {The Chigorin is a very interesting line. We will take a look at it in Chapter 2.}) (2... c5 {This line has become very popular nowadays. We have some strong novelties against it. It will be analyzed in Chapter 3.}) 3. Nf3 c5 {The Tarrasch Defense is a very solid choice for Black.} (3... a6 {The trendy 3...a6 line will be analyzed in Chapter 10, where our recommendation will be the solid yet venomous} 4. Bg5 $5 {[%csl Bg5]}) 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 {Here there are two lines:} Nf6 {This is the modern approach, which we will cover in Chapter 12.} (5... Nc6 {Classical variation, where our way will be} 6. dxc5 $5 {[%csl Cc5] and we will analyze it in Chapter 11.}) *

