{[%evp 0,39,27,28,28,-6,33,33,33,23,23,23,34,1,24,18,30,32,36,18,29,39,21,26,26,29,27,7,73,16,35,25,27,27,36,36,48,40,38,38,38,47]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 {The Albin Countergambit. Engine opinion remained very harsh towards this opening throughout the years, but it's still a playable sideline, and some strong players still use it from time to time (in blitz or rapid mostly).} 3. dxe5 {The main line is the most principled answer.} d4 {[%csl Bd4] The main line and most logical.} (3... Ne7 $5 {[%csl Be7] Modern sideline, used a few times by Magnus Carlsen, Dubov, Shimanov etc.} 4. f4 $5 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gg1f3] I think this is White's most interesting move, and you will for sure surprise your opponents here, because there is only 1 game out of 200.} ({If White goes for normal development, Black also has a more or less playable position:} 4. Nf3 Nbc6 5. e3 Bg4 {We are following Artemiev-Timofeev, 1-0, RUS-ch Blitz 2022.} 6. Qa4 Qd7 7. cxd5 Nxd5 $44 {Black has full compensation for the pawn.} 8. Bb5 Ndb4 $1 $13 {[%csl Bb4] Stronger than what happened in the game, the position is quite unclear.}) (4. cxd5 {The most logical move.} Qxd5 $1 {Black is ready to play an endgame.} 5. Qxd5 Nxd5 6. a3 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Rb4][%cal Ga3b4,Rd5b4] The best, to protect the b4 square.} Nc6 7. Nf3 g6 $1 {[%csl Bg6] Rare move, but strong one. Black must be very accurate, but long term they can somehow equalize, for example:} 8. e4 Nb6 9. Nc3 Bg7 10. Nb5 {looks very good for White, but Black can:} O-O $1 11. Nxc7 Rb8 $14 {[%csl Re5] Black has some compensation for the missing 2 pawns for now, but e5 is probably falling. White can play this endgame, but against a prepared strong opponent, it will be difficult to convert the material advantage.}) 4... Nbc6 {The most logical.} (4... Be6 {can be met with:} 5. e4 $1 {[%csl Be4] Strong idea.} dxe4 6. Qxd8+ Kxd8 7. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Re4] e4 falls and there is no compensation for the pawn.}) 5. Nf3 d4 $1 $146 {[%csl Bd4] The best move, but the position is already new.} (5... Be6 6. Bd2 $5 {[%csl Bd2] Very deep waiting move.} Nf5 {Logical.} (6... dxc4 $6 {is met with:} 7. e4 $1 $18 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5,Re6,Re7,Gf4][%cal Gf4f5] And Black is getting crushed.}) (6... d4 7. Na3 $16 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gd1b3,Ge1c1] looks also very good for White.}) 7. Nc3 d4 {Critical move, but it fails to:} (7... dxc4 $2 {Positional mistake.} 8. e4 $1 $18 {[%csl Ge4,Ge5,Re6,Gf4,Rf5][%cal Gf4f5] White wins.}) 8. Nd5 $1 {[%csl Gd5] The knight is strong here.} Bxd5 9. cxd5 Qxd5 10. g4 $1 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Rf5e3,Rf5e7] f5 knight is short on squares.} Nh4 11. Nxh4 $1 {Simple tactic.} Qxh1 12. Nf3 $1 $16 {[%csl Rh1][%cal Gd1b3,Ge1c1] White will finish development and win the stuck queen on h1.}) 6. a3 $5 {[%csl Ga3][%cal Gb2b4,Rc6b4] Useful move, to stop Nb4 and also prepare b4.} (6. e4 {Logical try, but the position is quite unclear after:} Bg4 7. h3 (7. Be2 {runs into:} d3 $1 $132 {[%csl Gd3,Re2] Very annoying tempo, and Black has counterplay.}) 7... Bxf3 8. Qxf3 g5 $1 {[%csl Re5,Rf4] To undermine the pawns.} 9. g3 Nb4 10. Rh2 h5 $1 $13 {[%cal Gh5h4] To follow up with h4, the game is extremely complex and unclear.}) 6... a5 7. e4 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Ra5,Ge4] We can go for this critical move now, since a3-a5 is clearly in White's favor.} Bg4 8. Be2 {[%csl Ga3][%cal Rd4d3,Ga3b4] No more d3 ideas, because b4 is protected.} (8. c5 $5 {Interesting alternative.} Ng6 9. h3 Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Bxc5 11. Bd3 $14 {[%cal Rg6h4,Gg7g5] Black will start their standard counterplay, but evaluation is good, so you can investigate.}) 8... Bxf3 $1 {Black seeks counterplay this way.} 9. Bxf3 g5 $1 {[%csl Re5,Rf4,Bg5] Standard reaction.} 10. e6 $1 {[%csl Ge6,Re8] To open the diagonal against the king.} gxf4 11. exf7+ Kxf7 12. Bxf4 {White's position looks almost winning, but Black can play positionally:} Ng6 $1 {[%csl Gc5,Ge5,Gf4,Gh4] The dark squares are a big asset.} 13. O-O $1 {[%cal Rg6f4,Gf3h5] Protecting the bishop tactically.} Kg7 14. e5 $5 {[%csl Be5][%cal Gf3c6] The most concrete try.} (14. Qd2 $5 $14 {[%csl Gd2][%cal Gd2f4] deserves attention, for a slight advantage.}) 14... Nxf4 15. Bxc6 Qg5 $1 {Black's idea.} (15... bxc6 $2 {Big mistake.} 16. Rxf4 $18 {[%csl Rg7] White should win.}) 16. g3 {The line continues:} Nh3+ $1 (16... Ng6 $6 17. Bg2 $16 {[%csl Gg1,Gg2][%cal Gb1d2] The king is safe, and White is better.}) 17. Kg2 bxc6 18. Nd2 $5 {[%csl Rh3] The knight is trapped, so White can finish development:} Be7 $3 {[%csl Be7] Black's only good move.} (18... Rb8 $2 {[%csl Rb2] looks like a logical tempo, but in fact it's losing:} 19. Ne4 $1 {[%csl Be4,Rg7][%cal Ge4g5,Gd1d4,Rg5e5,Bd1g4] We play for mate.} Rxb2+ 20. Kh1 $1 {[%csl Gh1] No more checks.} Qg6 21. Qxd4 $18 {[%csl Rb2,Rg7][%cal Gd4b2,Gd4g7] And Black can resign.}) 19. Kxh3 {Time to take the piece.} Rhf8 $1 {Black managed to survive, which is not a bad outcome I guess, but White is still slightly better, for example:} 20. Nf3 Qh6+ 21. Kg2 c5 22. Qd3 $14 {[%cal Ra8b8,Gb2b3] Pawn up, if White finishes development, the situation is very good, cause of the extra pawn, but engine can somehow hold it.}) (3... dxc4 $6 {Bad move.} 4. Qxd8+ Kxd8 5. Nc3 $16 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Gg1f3,Gc1g5,Gf3g5,Ge1c1] It's just a better endgame for White.}) 4. Nf3 Nc6 {Starting position of the line, White has a big choice:} 5. a3 $5 {[%csl Ba3][%cal Rf8b4] This is my recommendation, and I tried my best to refute this line for Black. The idea of the move is simple, to control the b4 square (against the annoying Bb4+).} (5. Nbd2 {Somewhat rare line, but it's used sometimes by strong players, and it's also recommended by the engine.} Nge7 6. Nb3 Ng6 $1 {[%cal Gg6e5] The best, to go after the 5 pawn.} (6... Nf5 $2 {[%csl Rf5] Mistake, played in a blitz game from 2018, Grischuk-Nepo, 1-0.} 7. e4 $1 {[%csl Ge4] Critical strike, and White had a huge advantage after:} dxe3 8. Qxd8+ Nxd8 9. fxe3 $16 {The endgame is unplayable for Black, the extra pawn and better pieces, secured Grischuk a convincing win.}) 7. Nbxd4 Ngxe5 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. e3 {Some time ago I was quite sure that this position should be at least slightly better for White, since Black has some compensation, but obviously not full.} Bc5 10. Bd2 $5 {More ambitious try, we give up the pawn immediately, for quick development.} (10. Be2 {Most logical move, played in Sychev-Shevchenko, 0-1, Wch Rapid 2023. But Black showed a very nice way:} Qg5 $1 {[%csl Rg2,Gg5][%cal Gg5g2] Very good tempo move and Black has serious counterplay.} 11. Kf1 $1 $146 {[%csl Gf1] The best move.} (11. O-O $2 {was played in the game, but it's not a good idea.} Bh3 $1 12. Bf3 O-O-O $1 $36 {[%csl Gc5,Gd8,Ge5,Gg5,Gh3] Every piece comes into play, and Shevchenko had an easy to play initiative, that transformed into a full point.}) 11... O-O 12. Bd2 Rd8 {Position becomes concrete:} 13. b4 $1 Bf8 14. h4 $1 Qe7 15. h5 h6 $1 {To stop h6.} 16. Qc2 Bg4 {Black has active pieces, which secure him enough compensation.} 17. Bc3 c5 $1 {[%csl Bc5] Key move.} 18. bxc5 Qxc5 $44 {Black should be normal.}) (10. Qc2 $6 {was played in the game Wojtaszek-L'Ami, 1-0, FIDE Grand Swiss 2023, but I don't like this move.} O-O 11. Nb3 Bb4+ 12. Bd2 Bxd2+ 13. Nxd2 Re8 14. O-O-O Qh4 $1 $44 {Improvement over the game, and Black has compensation.} 15. Nf3 Nxf3 16. gxf3 Bh3 $1 {[%csl Bh3] Key move.} 17. Bxh3 Qxh3 18. f4 Rad8 $11 {[%csl Rh1,Rh2,Gh3] White is a bit stuck with the rook on h1.}) 10... Bxd4 11. exd4 Qxd4 12. Bc3 $1 {[%csl Gc3,Rg7][%cal Gc3g7] The point.} Qf4 13. Qd2 Qe4+ {This is more forcing.} (13... Qxd2+ {The endgame is quite unpleasant for Black.} 14. Kxd2 f6 15. Re1 O-O {White is slightly better, but I guess can also play this endgame.} 16. Bxe5 (16. c5 $5 $14 {[%csl Gc5] Positional move, to active the f1 bishop, should be a bit better for White.}) 16... fxe5 17. f3 Bf5 $1 18. Rxe5 Rad8+ $44 {Compensation for Black.}) 14. Qe2 Nd3+ 15. Kd2 Qxe2+ 16. Kxe2 Nf4+ 17. Kf3 Ne6 {The line was forced until here, and once again, White is slightly better, but with precise play, Black could somehow hold the game.} 18. Rd1 $146 {[%csl Gd1] Just useful move.} b6 19. Bd3 h5 $1 {[%csl Gg4,Bh5][%cal Rc8b7,Ge6g5,Gh5h4] Good move, Black has the idea of Bb7+ and in case of Kg3-h4.} 20. Ke3 $14 {[%cal Gf2f3,Ge3f2] However, I would pick White anytime of the week here.}) 5... Nge7 {The old main line.} (5... a5 $6 {Bad move.} 6. Nbd2 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Ra5] White gets an improve version of the 5.Nbd2 line, for example:} Nge7 7. Nb3 Ng6 $6 {This is no compensation anymore.} (7... Nf5 {is once again met with:} 8. e4 $1 $16 {[%cal Gd1d8] Leading to a very good endgame.}) 8. Nbxd4 Ngxe5 9. Nxe5 Nxe5 10. Bf4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ga3,Rb4,Re5,Bf4][%cal Rf8b4] Without the a3 a5 inclusion, this move was not possible, because of the annoying Bb4+, but here White is simply a pawn up.}) (5... Bg4 $2 {Common line, but it's quite bad.} 6. Nbd2 Nge7 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Nxf3 Ng6 {Black regains the pawn, but it doesn't matter:} 9. e6 $1 {[%csl Be6] Good positional reaction.} fxe6 10. g3 $16 {[%csl Rd4,Re6,Rg6][%cal Gf1g2,Gh3h4,Gd1d3,Gb2b4] The position is just unplayable for Black, White has a huge advantage thanks to the pair of bishops and better structure.}) (5... Be6 $2 {[%csl Rc4] Black tries to attack the pawn on c4, but we can just ignore it:} 6. b4 $1 {[%csl Ga3,Gb4] Another point of 5.a3.} Bxc4 7. Nbd2 Be6 8. Bb2 $16 {[%csl Gb2,Gd2,Rd4,Gf3][%cal Gb4b5,Gg2g3] White is too ahead in development, b5 is a big threat, just huge advantage.}) (5... g6 $5 {A very rare line, it started to appear on the high level a few years ago, but of course, Black can enter it only with strong engine preparation.} 6. Bg5 {The most concrete.} (6. h3 $5 $146 {Good positional way.} Bg7 7. e4 $1 {[%csl Gh3][%cal Rc8g4] And h3 is useful since it stops Bg4.} Nxe5 $6 8. Nxd4 $16 {White is better.}) 6... Be7 $1 {Only critical move.} (6... Qd7 $6 {The queen is misplaced here.} 7. Bf4 Bg7 8. g3 $16 {Good situation for White.}) 7. Bxe7 Qxe7 {Necessary.} (7... Ngxe7 $6 {too slow.} 8. Nbd2 O-O (8... a5 9. Ne4 $16 {[%csl Ge4,Rg6][%cal Ge4f6]}) 9. b4 $16 {[%cal Re7g6] Black can't regain the pawn, White is just better.}) 8. Nxd4 Nxe5 9. Nc3 Nf6 {So this is the point of the line, just give up a pawn, and play for some engine like compensation. But of course, from a human point of view, White is just better.} 10. e4 $5 {Principled.} (10. e3 $5 {Very good option, if you feel that your opponent is not prepared.} O-O 11. Be2 Rd8 {was played in some email games:} 12. Qb3 Bg4 $1 $44 {[%cal Re1g1,Gc7c5] The game continued down a forcing path, and probably Black has compensation.}) 10... O-O 11. Qe2 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Ge1c1] The point is to castle long and crush.} c5 $1 {[%csl Bc5] The only good option, played in one email game.} (11... Rd8 $6 {Logical, but wrong.} 12. O-O-O c5 13. Nc2 $16 {[%csl Gc2,Gd5][%cal Gc2e3] White is just better.}) 12. Nf3 $1 {[%csl Gf3] The best.} (12. Nc2 $6 {It doesn't work, because of:} b5 $3 $13 {[%csl Bb5][%cal Rc4b5,Gf8d8] Very strong move, position is unclear.}) 12... Rd8 $1 {[%csl Gd8,Re1][%cal Gd8d1] Black should stop White from castling.} (12... Bg4 $6 {allows White to finish development:} 13. O-O-O $16 {[%cal Ge2e3] White is just pawn up.}) 13. Nd5 Nxd5 14. cxd5 $146 {This strange position occurs, with no games.} Re8 $1 {[%csl Be8] The best.} 15. Nd2 c4 $1 {Very engine stuff.} 16. Qe3 Ng4 $1 17. Qd4 Qf6 $1 {[%csl Gf6,Gg4] Very nice point from Black, I don't know if anybody will ever find this.} 18. Qxf6 Nxf6 19. f3 c3 $1 {[%csl Gc3] Important intermezzo.} 20. bxc3 Nxd5 {Black reached a pawn down endgame, with some slight chances to hold it.} 21. Bc4 $1 {Good tempo.} Nb6 $1 {The best.} (21... Ne3 $2 {Logical but also mistake.} 22. Kf2 $1 $16 {[%cal Re3c4,Gd2c4] Big advantage.}) (21... Nxc3 $2 {loses material.} 22. Rc1 $1 $18 {[%cal Rc3a4,Gc4b5] The knight is trapped.}) 22. a4 $14 {[%cal Ga4a5] It's a good time to stop, okay, an engine will hold it, in practical game, White should win, 3 times out of 4 this endgame.}) 6. b4 $5 {[%csl Gb4] Not always old line is bad line, this time we can follow it:} Ng6 7. Bb2 a5 $1 {[%csl Ga5,Rb4] Strong players usually include this, to undermine the White structure a bit. This line was used very often by GM Morozevich in short time controls, with good results against top level GMs.} (7... Ngxe5 {or 7...Ncxe5 leads to the same.} 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. e3 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Rd4,Re5,Gf1][%cal Gf1c4,Gb2e5] Good move, to protect the c4 pawn before capturing on d4.} Be6 10. Bxd4 Nxc4 11. Qc2 {White has easy play:} Nd6 12. Bd3 Qg5 {[%cal Rg5g2] Black tries the usual idea, but it doesn't work well:} 13. O-O $1 $16 {[%cal Gb1c3,Gf2f4] This time we are not afraid of Bh3.} Bh3 $4 14. f4 $1 $18 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Gc2g2,Rg5g4,Gf1f3] The queen protects g2, and White wins a piece.}) 8. b5 {Necessary.} Ncxe5 9. Nxe5 $5 {[%csl Ce5] More ambitious to play the middlegame.} (9. Qxd4 $5 {The endgame is also interesting for White.} Qxd4 10. Bxd4 Nxc4 11. e3 Nd6 12. Nbd2 $14 {[%csl Rc7,Gd2,Gd4,Gf3,Rf8,Rg7][%cal Gb1c1,Ga1b1] White has good pieces and development, and enjoys a small advnatage.}) 9... Nxe5 10. Bxd4 Nxc4 11. e3 {The situation is quite similar to 7...Ncxe5, but the structure is a bit in Black's favor thanks to the a5-b5 inclusion,} Be6 12. Qc2 Nd6 13. Nd2 $5 {[%csl Gd2] Solid move.} (13. Bd3 $6 {Don't hurry with this move, because after:} Qg5 $1 $132 {[%csl Rb5,Rg2,Gg5][%cal Rg5g2,Rg5b5] Compared to having a pawn on b4, this is now a double attack.}) 13... Qg5 {[%csl Rb5,Gf1][%cal Gg5b5] Thanks to having a bishop on f1, this only attacks the b5 pawn.} 14. Qb2 {[%csl Gb2,Rg7][%cal Gb2g7] Just defend it and put some pressure on g7 as well.} Nf5 15. Be5 Bd6 {We are following the engine line:} 16. Nf3 Bxe5 $1 17. Qxe5 Qf6 {Engine suggest to go for the endgame, but it's quite unpleasant.} (17... Qe7 18. Bd3 $14 {White is slightly better.}) 18. Qxf6 gxf6 19. Bd3 O-O-O 20. Ke2 $14 {[%csl Rc7,Rf6][%cal Ga1c1] White is slightly better, very easy to play, and a lot of targets to focus on.} *

