{[%evp 0,35,30,30,20,4,3,3,68,-15,15,-31,2,8,-31,-32,-49,-64,7,-69,-15,-15,20,-60,-21,5,37,34,35,24,59,50,50,37,55,38,59,-3]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 Nc6 {The Chigorin Defense violates several classical principles: Black does not support the central d5 pawn and blocks the c-pawn. Still, from the engine’s perspective, this line is entirely sound and remains a very playable choice.} 3. Nc3 Nf6 {The modern main line.} (3... dxc4 {Black's old mainline, but it's bad.} 4. d5 Ne5 {Statistical main line.} (4... Nb8 {Best for the engine, but White is just better after} 5. e4 {[%cal Gf1c4]} e5 6. Bxc4 $16 {[%csl Rb8] Very good version of the QGA 3.e4 Nc6.}) (4... Na5 $2 {fails tactically:} 5. Qa4+ $1 c6 6. b4 $1 {[%csl Ra5,Bb4] Typical reaction.} b5 {Most players tried to play an endgame with a piece down.} (6... cxb3 7. axb3 e6 8. Bd2 $1 $18 {[%cal Ga4a5] Important.} (8. Qxa5 $4 {Not immediately.} Qxa5 9. Rxa5 Bb4 $1 $19 {[%csl Ra5,Rc3][%cal Gb4c3,Gb4a5] The point.}) 8... b6 {is met with:} 9. b4 $18 {[%cal Ra5c4,Ga4c6] And White wins.}) 7. Qxa5 Qxa5 8. bxa5 b4 9. Nd1 cxd5 {[%csl Gb4,Gc4,Gd5] Visually, some compensation exists, but slowly, White can convert the extra piece, for example:} 10. e4 $1 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Rd5e4] Good reaction.} e6 11. exd5 exd5 12. Ne3 Nf6 13. Nf3 {We can blockade the passed pawns.} Be6 14. Bb2 Be7 (14... c3 $2 15. Bc1 $18 {[%csl Rb4,Rc3][%cal Gf1d3] The pawns are stuck, and slowly White can collect them.}) 15. g3 O-O 16. Bg2 Rfc8 17. Bd4 $16 {[%cal Ge1g1] There is some compensation, but we are out of theory for a long time, and Black had to find engine moves to get here.}) 5. f4 $1 {[%csl Re5] This almost looks like a Mirrored Alekhine Defense, but in fact, here the knight is in even more trouble.} Ng4 $6 {The main line, but it is close to being refuted.} (5... Ng6 6. e4 {Black has troubles finishing development:} e6 7. dxe6 Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 {[%cal Rc8e6]} fxe6 9. Bxc4 {[%cal Gg1f3] The best Black can achieve, but the endgame is just bad.} Bd7 10. Nf3 O-O-O 11. Kc2 $16 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gh2h4,Gf3g5] A lot of ideas for White, Black is seriously worse.}) (5... Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6] This is a logical try, to reroute the knight to b6.} 6. e4 Nb6 7. a4 a5 8. Be3 e6 9. Qc2 $5 {[%csl Gc2] Only 1 game out of 100, and it was also played in corr. chess. Very principled.} (9. Bxb6 $6 {The most common move, but the position is quite unclear after:} cxb6 10. Bxc4 Bb4 11. Bb5+ Kf8 $13 {White should have a small advantage, but Black can play it as well.}) 9... exd5 10. Bxb6 cxb6 11. O-O-O $1 $36 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gc3d5,Gf1c4] This is the point, White develops a fast initiative against the king on e8.}) 6. e4 e5 7. Nf3 Bc5 8. h3 $1 {[%csl Bh3] Key move, and Black can't make use of the knight jumps.} Nf2 {Critical, but fails to:} (8... Ne3 9. Bxe3 Bxe3 10. fxe5 $18 {[%cal Gf1c4] No compensation, White collects material and wins.}) 9. Qa4+ $1 Bd7 10. Qxc4 {[%csl Gc4,Rc5] The point.} Nxh1 11. Qxc5 $18 {[%csl Rh1] The knight on h1 will never get back into the game, according to the engine, White has a decisive advantage already.}) (3... e5 $2 {Bad line.} 4. cxd5 Nxd4 5. e3 Nf5 6. e4 $1 {[%csl Ge4] Important to play it immediately, so that Black cannot comfortably play Nfe7.} (6. Nf3 $6 {Most common, but Black gets a playable position after:} Bd6 7. e4 Nfe7 $1 $132 {[%csl Be7]}) 6... Nd4 (6... Nd6 7. f4 $16 {[%cal Gg1f3] Nf3 next with a big advantage.}) (6... Nh4 7. g3 Ng6 8. h4 $1 $16 {[%csl Yg5,Rg6][%cal Gh4h5] Standard reaction, the knight is misplaced.}) 7. Be3 Bc5 8. Nge2 $16 {Bluebaum-Finegold, 2025.}) (3... e6 {This is a solid approach.} 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. a3 $5 {[%csl Ba3][%cal Rf8b4,Gb2b4] I think this is the most interesting approach, to stop Bb4, and somewhere prepare the b4 expansion.} (5. Bg5 {The most common try, but Black should be more or less fine after:} dxc4 $132 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Rc6d4] And at least the knight on c6 is not so stupid anymore.}) 5... Be7 {The most common, but White can also just finish development:} (5... dxc4 6. e4 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Rf8b4] This is the point of a3.} Na5 7. Bxc4 {Positional idea.} Nxc4 8. Qa4+ c6 9. Qxc4 $14 {Black has two bishops, but White has center and better development.}) (5... Ne4 $5 {Rare move, but it was played in the recent game Chigaev-Boyer, EU-ch 2025.} 6. Qc2 Nxc3 7. Qxc3 a5 $1 {[%cal Gf8b4] Bb4 is a threat, and a5 is in general a good move, using our knowledge from the Catalan.} 8. Bf4 dxc4 9. Qxc4 Bd6 10. Bg3 h5 $1 {[%csl Bh5][%cal Bh5h4] This is the point of Black's preparation, with logical moves we reach this critical position.} 11. e3 $5 {[%csl Ge3] I think this is more interesting.} (11. e4 {was Chigaev's choice, but after:} h4 $1 $13 {[%cal Rg3d6,Gc7d6] Players agreed to a draw a few moves later.}) 11... h4 12. Be5 $1 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rf7f6] First we provoke f6.} f6 (12... Bxe5 $1 $146 {This is probably the best, but not easy to play.} 13. dxe5 Qd5 14. Qf4 a4 15. Rd1 Qa5+ 16. Rd2 $14 {[%csl Re8] For the engine, this is playable also for Black, but from a human point of view, it looks riskier.}) 13. Bxd6 cxd6 (13... Qxd6 $6 {Positional mistake.} 14. h3 $16 {[%csl Rc6,Rc7] Bad structure for Black.}) 14. h3 $14 {[%csl Rb5] Black's structure is more or less okay, but still some holes exist, and White definitely has a slight advantage.}) 6. Bf4 {[%csl Gf4] Good square for the bishop.} O-O (6... dxc4 {is once again met with:} 7. e4 $1 Na5 8. Bxc4 $14 {[%cal Ra5c4,Gd1a4] Tactical point, White is slightly better.}) 7. e3 $14 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Yb2b4] The knight is just misplaced, b4 is our long term plan, Black didn't equalize here.}) 4. Bg5 $5 {[%csl Gg5] This move is quite interesting, to put pressure on the d5 pawn.} (4. Nf3 {The main line however is still very playable for White.} dxc4 {Most principled.} (4... e6 5. a3 $5 {transposes to 3...e6.}) 5. e4 {White grabs the full center.} (5. d5 {This is more straight-forward try.} Na5 6. Qa4+ c6 7. b4 $1 {[%csl Gb4] Standard reaction.} b5 $1 {Black's only critical try.} 8. Qxa5 Qxa5 9. bxa5 b4 {[%csl Rf3,Gf6] Compared to 3...dxc4, our knight is quite early on f3, because we won't have e4.} 10. Na4 $5 {This is the most interesting try, if you want to keep the extra piece.} (10. Nd1 $6 {I don't like.} cxd5 $132 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Re2e4] We can't push e4, and Black should have full compensation I think.}) (10. dxc6 $5 {[%csl Gc6] This is a risk free choice.} bxc3 11. e3 Ba6 $1 {The only good move.} 12. Ne5 e6 13. Nxc4 $5 {[%cal Re8c8,Gc4b6] If long castle, White has Nb6! and in case of:} Bb5 {The only move that has occured.} 14. Nd6+ Bxd6 15. Bxb5 a6 16. Ba4 Ke7 17. Ke2 $14 {[%csl Rc3,Gc6][%cal Gh1d1,Ga1b1] For the engine, Black has full compensation, but White is not risking anything on the other hand, and the c3 pawn is more vulnerable than the c6 one.}) 10... cxd5 11. a3 $1 {To force b3.} b3 12. Bb2 $13 {[%csl Gb2,Rb3,Rc4,Rd5][%cal Gb2e5] The pawns are nicely blockaded, but they are anyways quite strong, it's difficult to break this chain. Position is very interesting and playable for both sides. There are more details in the video lesson, but if you want to use it in your own games, you should have your own analysis, because it's difficult to see everything.}) 5... Bg4 6. d5 $5 {Decent option as well, used a few by GM Bluebaum.} (6. Be3 {The main line.} e6 7. Bxc4 Bb4 8. Qd3 {This is definitely playable for White, and some slight advantage should exist.} O-O (8... Bxf3 $6 {Positional mistake now.} 9. gxf3 O-O 10. O-O-O $1 $40 {[%csl Gc1,Rg8][%cal Gh1g1,Gg1g8,Gh2h4] White has attacking chances, and the king is better on c1 than on g1 clearly.}) 9. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Gd2] Good prophylaxis.} (9. O-O $6 {allows:} Bxf3 $1 10. gxf3 Nh5 $132 {[%csl Rf1,Gg8][%cal Rh1g1,Rg1g8] And compared to having the king still on e1, White can't use the g-file for an attack, and the king is also unsafe.}) 9... a6 {Concrete try.} 10. f3 b5 $1 {[%csl Bb5] Black's idea.} 11. Bb3 Bh5 {The line is semi-forced, I just played natural moves for both sides:} 12. Bc2 Bg6 13. a3 Bd6 $1 {[%cal Ge6e5] with e5 idea.} (13... Ba5 $6 14. Nb3 $14 {[%csl Ra5] The bishop is not so well placed.}) 14. O-O e5 15. d5 $14 {[%cal Rc6d4,Gd2b3] Slight advantage for White. I prefer our structure, Black is in actually quite a risky situation, because one wrong move, and Black could end up in a seriously worse position.} (15. dxe5 $5 {also deserves attention.})) 6... Ne5 7. Be3 $5 {More tricky.} (7. Bf4 {The main try, but Black has a strong move:} Nfd7 $1 $132 {[%cal Re5f3,Ge7e5] With serious counterplay.}) 7... a6 $1 {Black's best move, played in the high level encounter Keymer-Abdusattorov, 0-1, Prague Masters 2024.} 8. h3 Nxf3+ 9. gxf3 Bh5 10. Bxc4 e5 $1 {Nodirbek was very well prepared, and in fact it took White by surprise.} 11. dxe6 {The best try for White, and I am sure that Abdusattorov analyzed the following endgame:} (11. Be2 $6 {was Keymer's move, but it's strange.} Bd6 $1 $36 {Black overtakes the initiative.}) 11... Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 fxe6 13. Ke2 Bb4 $1 {And on big depths, the enigne should hold, but of course, even here, it's quite unpleasant to play with Black:} 14. Bd4 $1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gd4g7,Ge2e3] Good centralizing move.} (14. Bxe6 {is met with:} Bxc3 $1 {[%csl Bc3] Black's point.} 15. bxc3 Nxe4 $11 {[%csl Re2,Ge4,Re6,Gh5][%cal Rh5f3,Re4c3,Re4g5] And position is equal.}) 14... Bf7 {[%cal Gf6h5] looks like the most logical.} (14... Bxc3 $6 {[%csl Gd4] Not so good now, since the bishop is already on the diagonal.} 15. Bxc3 Nxe4 16. Bxg7 $14 {[%cal Gh1g1,Rh8g8] White should have a slight advantage.}) 15. Rhg1 $5 {White has many options.} Nh5 16. Be5 $36 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf3f4] Not much, but some initiative definitely exists. Plus it's not everyday, that you have to face GM Abdusattorov with exquisite theory preparation.}) 4... Ne4 {The main line, but White has a fantastic resource:} (4... dxc4 {[%csl Gc4] This is the easiest, if Black wants to just have a game.} 5. e3 h6 6. Bxf6 $1 {[%csl Bf6] The correct way.} (6. Bh4 {is met with:} e5 $1 $11 {With a normal position.}) 6... exf6 7. Bxc4 Bd6 $14 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Yg1f3,Yg1e2] Black has a standard position, and I guess Black shouldn't be too sad about it. Still, White should be slightly better.} 8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Ne7 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Ge7g6] Black should improve the knight.} (9... a6 {Common plan.} 10. a3 $5 {[%csl Ga3][%cal Gc4a2] White has infinite useful moves.} Ne7 11. Rc1 b5 12. Ba2 Bb7 13. Qe2 Qd7 14. Rfd1 $14 {[%cal Gf3e1,Ge1d3,Ya2b1] White has very easy play, Black is solid, but short on active counterplay.}) 10. h3 c6 11. a3 f5 12. Rc1 {White has a risk free advantage.} Ng6 13. g3 $5 {[%csl Gg3,Rg6][%cal Gg1g2,Gh3h4] Against the knight.} f4 {The most logical.} 14. Qd3 $1 {[%csl Gc4,Rg6,Rg8][%cal Gd3g6] Good tempo.} Kh8 15. exf4 Bxh3 16. Rfe1 $14 {[%cal Gf3e5] Ne5 next and White is better.}) (4... e6 {Black finishes development, but it's not so principled.} 5. e3 (5. Nf3 {don't hurry with this.} dxc4 $5 {Extra option for Black.}) 5... Be7 6. Rc1 O-O 7. Nf3 $14 {[%csl Rc6] The knight on c6 is just misplaced, White has a slight advantage for free.}) 5. e3 $3 {[%csl Be3] Brilliant idea.} f6 $5 $146 {Probably the best option, but not an easy move.} (5... Nxc3 $6 6. bxc3 $16 {[%csl Rc6] White is just positionally better.}) (5... Nxg5 $2 {fails to:} 6. cxd5 $1 Nb8 7. h4 $16 {[%csl Gd5,Rg5][%cal Rg5e4] The knight is trapped, the best is Ne4, but White will have a development advantage in that case.}) (5... Bf5 $6 {[%cal Ge4c3,Gd8d7,Ge8c8] Black aims to finish development.} 6. Nge2 $5 {[%csl Gc3,Be2][%cal Re4g5,Ge2c3] Another fancy move, to support the c3 knight.} Nxg5 {What else?} 7. cxd5 Nb8 8. Ng3 $1 {[%csl Rf5,Gg3][%cal Gg3e4,Gg3f5] Key tempo to control the e4 square.} e6 9. h4 $16 {White is better.}) 6. Bh4 e5 $1 {[%csl Be5] Black's idea.} 7. Nxd5 Be6 8. f3 Nd6 $44 {[%cal Gd1c2] Black has compensation for the pawn, but the position is new, so White can for sure fight for the advantage. For example, the game continues with:} 9. Qc2 {The best engine line.} Nf5 10. Bf2 Nb4 $1 {[%csl Bb4] Concrete stuff.} 11. Qb3 {This is simpler.} (11. Qa4+ {is met with:} b5 $3 $13 {[%csl Bb5] Engine move.}) 11... Nxd5 12. cxd5 Bxd5 13. Qa4+ {[%cal Rc7c6,Ge3e4] White is ready for e4.} Bc6 $1 {Forced.} 14. Bb5 Bd7 $1 {And we can go to an endgame:} 15. Bxd7+ Qxd7 16. Qxd7+ Kxd7 17. dxe5 fxe5 18. Ke2 $14 {[%cal Gg1h3,Gh1d1,Ga1c1] Very simple play for White, not risking anything. So with this we can conclude that Chigorin is playable, but it requires a lot of knowledge for Black, to achieve this position was not easy, to say the least.} *

