{[%evp 0,47,26,27,27,4,39,39,49,49,51,54,46,44,37,36,45,47,47,5,5,33,42,65,24,19,19,25,17,25,25,22,23,-3,-3,-15,-22,-9,-19,-30,-25,-26,-1,26,34,-6,-6,-56,-6,-31]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c5 {This is a very serious line, and you can expect to face it also in classical chess, if your opponent is well prepared. Some years ago, engines' opinion was that White should be slightly better, but now it became more difficult to find an objective advantage. However, White can pose a lot of practical problems:} 3. cxd5 $1 {[%csl Bd5] Objectively the best move, other tries are interesting, but they transpose to serious openings, like Tarrasch, for example.} Qxd5 {Necessary move.} (3... Nf6 $6 {This is very often used by GM Nakamura, but it's not the best.} 4. e4 $1 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4] Very good reply, supporting the d5 pawn.} Nxe4 {Necessary.} 5. dxc5 Qa5+ $1 {[%csl Ba5] The best option.} (5... Nxc5 6. Nc3 {White has a very good positional advantage, for example:} e5 7. Nf3 Bd6 {Black tries to play for blockade, but the whole construction is not so good.} 8. Bg5 $1 {Good tempo, used by GM Gyimesi.} f6 9. Be3 O-O 10. b4 $1 $146 {[%csl Gb4,Rc5] Improvement over the game.} Ncd7 11. a3 $16 {[%csl Rb8,Rd6,Rd7][%cal Gc3b5] Black has serious troubles coordinating.}) 6. Bd2 Nxd2 (6... Qxc5 $4 {Common blunder.} 7. Qa4+ $1 $18 {[%csl Re4,Re8][%cal Ga4e8,Ga4e4] Winning a piece.}) 7. Qxd2 {White aims for the endgame.} Qxd2+ $5 {[%csl Bd2] This is probably the best try.} (7... Qxc5 {is met with:} 8. Na3 $1 {[%csl Ba3][%cal Ga1c1] Key move.} Qb6 9. Rc1 {White is too fast with developing the pieces, for example:} Bd7 10. Nc4 Qf6 11. Nf3 g6 12. Nce5 Bg7 {Black needs one more tempo to be fine, but:} 13. Bb5 $3 $18 {[%csl Gb5,Rc8,Re8][%cal Gc1c8] Cute tactic, and Black can resign.}) 8. Nxd2 g6 9. Rc1 $16 {We are following the game Salem-Madaminov, 1-0, Qatar Masters op 2024. White should be better.}) 4. Nf3 {The most critical line.} cxd4 5. Nc3 $1 {[%csl Rd5] Using the tempo against the vulnerable queen.} Qa5 {The main move, it is the favorite line of GM Mamedyarov, he has 40+ games played in the online database!} (5... Qd8 {too pessimistic.} 6. Qxd4 $16 {[%cal Gf3d4] Don't be fooled that the structure is symmetrical, White has a lot of free tempi.}) 6. Nxd4 Nf6 $1 {The best move.} (6... e5 $2 {Positional mistake, but also fails tactically:} 7. Nb3 Qc7 8. Nb5 $1 {[%csl Bb5,Rc7][%cal Gb5c7] Key move.} Qb6 {was played in the game Basso-Bossi, 1-0, Bassano del Grappa Spring 2021.} 9. e4 $1 {[%cal Gc1e3] White has a winning position already.} Bb4+ 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 $18 {[%cal Gb5d6] Nd6+ followed, and Pier won in the next 10 moves.}) 7. a3 $5 {This move is very rare, but very venomous. It's an useful prophylactic and also supports the b4 push.} (7. g3 {The main move, but it doesn't really offer an advantage:} e5 $1 {[%csl Ge5,Gf6,Rg3] With the g3-Nf6 moves included, this makes more sense:} 8. Nb3 Qc7 {[%csl Rh1][%cal Rc3b5,Gc7c6] The difference is that Nb5 doesn't work now.} 9. Bg2 Bb4 $1 $132 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gb4e1] To pin the knight, Black is doing okay, and in fact Mamedyarov scored pretty well with this line in blitz games.}) (7. Nb3 {was what I analyzed some years ago:} Qc7 8. Nb5 $5 Qe5 9. e4 $1 {[%csl Be4] Fantastic move, and engines were almost refuting the line for Black, but times have changed.} a6 {The best.} 10. Nc3 Nc6 11. f4 Qc7 $1 $146 {[%csl Bc7] Engines have found this provocative move, and made it work out.} (11... Qd6 $6 {The only move that has occured, but of course, the endgame is better for White.} 12. Qxd6 exd6 13. Be3 $14 {''How much better?'' is another question, but White is better.}) 12. e5 Bg4 $1 13. Be2 Rd8 $1 {Forced line-} 14. Bd2 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 Nd5 16. e6 $1 {[%csl Ge6] This was considered much better for White some years ago, but now engines hold the position after:} fxe6 $1 17. O-O g6 $1 {[%csl Bg6] Key point.} 18. Qxe6 Nf6 $132 {[%cal Gd8d6,Gf8g7] And it's just playable for Black, engine doesn't care about structure or development, everything is temporary in life.}) 7... e5 $1 {This is principled.} (7... g6 $6 {was played 3 times by Mamedyarov, but it's a bad move.} 8. b4 $5 {[%csl Bb4] The most interesting plan.} Qd8 9. Bf4 $1 $146 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Re7e5] To stop e5 and prepare Nb5.} Nh5 {The best.} (9... Bg7 $6 {possible, but bad.} 10. Ndb5 $1 $16 {[%cal Gb5c7] Black loses material most likely.}) 10. Be5 $1 {[%csl Be5] Good tempo.} Bg7 11. Bxg7 Nxg7 12. g3 $16 {[%cal Gf1g2] Black can try to play this, but for sure it's not pleasant. White is better.}) 8. Nb3 Qc7 9. Nb5 $5 $146 {[%csl Bb5] This is our main recommendation. It's a novelty, and Black must have very serious knowledge and understanding, just to SURVIVE the opening phase!} (9. Bg5 {This line was used 2 times by GM Matlakov and once by GM Artemiev.} Be7 $1 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Ge7f6] The best move, to support the structure.} (9... Be6 $2 {was Mamedyarov's choice in all 3 games, but it's a mistake.} 10. Bxf6 $1 {We transform the development advantage in a positional one.} gxf6 11. Nd5 $1 {[%csl Gd5] This was Matlakov's preparation.} Qd8 12. e4 f5 $5 $146 {[%csl Gf5] The only chance, to improve the structure.} (12... Nc6 13. Bc4 $16 {Matlakov-Mamedyarov, 1-0, Titled Tuesday 2020. White is seriously better.}) 13. Bc4 $1 {Good move, we don't care about the e4 pawn.} fxe4 14. Qc2 $1 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Rf7f5] Key move. Black doesn't have time to defend the pawn.} Nc6 (14... f5 $2 15. O-O $18 {[%csl Re8][%cal Ga1d1,Gf2f3] White is just winning, the threats are too big.}) 15. Rd1 $16 {[%csl Gd1] White is better also here.}) 10. Bxf6 $5 $146 {The best chance to fight for something.} (10. Rc1 {was played in the only game that reached this position.} Nc6 $132 {[%csl Yc1,Gc6] Black is doing fine, I think Nc6 is more useful than Rc1.}) 10... Bxf6 11. Nd5 Qd6 $1 {[%csl Gd6,Gh8][%cal Gf6d8] The best move, to leave the d8 square for the bishop or eventually the rook.} (11... Qd8 12. g3 $14 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gf1g2] This is at least slight advantage for White, with very good control in the center.}) 12. Nc5 $5 {[%cal Rd6c5,Ga1c1,Gc5e4] Principled try, using the small tactic.} Bd8 $1 {Only move.} 13. g3 O-O 14. Rc1 Nc6 15. Bg2 f5 {The position is quite interesting, but playable for both sides, for example:} 16. O-O e4 17. f3 $36 {Potentially, White could have a small advantage, but Black is also fighting.}) 9... Qc6 $1 {The most logical move and the best.} (9... Qe7 $6 {[%csl Re7,Rf8] This is wrong from a positional point of view, how will Black finish development?} 10. g3 $5 {[%cal Gf1g2] Positional choice.} Nc6 11. Bg2 Be6 12. O-O Rd8 13. Qc2 {[%csl Gc2,Re8] Black is stuck for now, and in fact the tactical ideas are already brewing for White:} Rc8 $1 {[%csl Bc8] Black has to follow the queen.} (13... Nd5 $2 {looks like the most logical, to defend from Bxc6.} 14. Na5 $3 {[%csl Ba5] Fantastic resource.} Nxa5 15. Bxd5 $1 $18 {[%cal Re6d5,Gb5c7] Nc7+ follows, White wins.}) 14. Nc3 g6 15. Be3 $5 {[%csl Yc5,Ge3] To use the c5 square.} (15. Bg5 $5 $14 {also very interesting.}) 15... Ng4 $1 {The best.} (15... Bg7 16. Rac1 $16 {[%cal Re8g8,Ge3c5] White is seriously better, because castle is still impossible.}) 16. Nd5 $1 {[%csl Gd5] Immediately jump in.} Qd7 $5 {Black must move the queen.} (16... Bxd5 $2 17. Bxd5 $16 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Rg4e3,Gf2e3,Ge3c5] White is much better, with this monster bishop on d5.}) 17. Qd2 {And now go for the tactical sequence:} Bxd5 $1 {But okay, for a human, this is close to unfindable. Just tough decision after tough decision on each move.} 18. Bxd5 Nd4 $1 {[%csl Gd4,Rd5] The point.} 19. Bf3 {White can still play for a small advantage:} Nxf3+ 20. exf3 Nxe3 21. Qxe3 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Re5][%cal Ge3a7,Ge3e5] White can win one pawn, or play for more:} Bg7 22. Rfd1 $5 {[%csl Rd7] Play for the maximum.} Qb5 23. a4 $1 Qb6 $1 {[%csl Bb6] One more only move for Black.} (23... Qb4 $6 {runs into:} 24. Rd5 $1 $16 {[%csl Rb4,Re5][%cal Gd5b5,Gd5e5] With a double threat.}) 24. Rac1 Rxc1 25. Rxc1 O-O 26. Qxb6 axb6 27. Rc7 $14 {[%csl Rb6,Rb7,Gg7][%cal Gb3d2,Gd2c4,Re5e4] White will end up in an endgame, where Black's only chance now is to for e4! and White can win a pawn and try to convert.}) 10. e3 {[%cal Gb3a5] White is ready for Na5, which is actually an annoying threat.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Bg4] Black must understand to first include f3 (not easy without an engine).} (10... Be6 $6 {The most logical move, but in fact, White is positionally better.} 11. Na5 $1 {[%csl Ba5] Key idea of the line.} Qb6 12. Nc4 $1 {[%csl Rb5,Gc4,Gf1][%cal Gc4e5,Rb6b5,Gc4d6] The point, Qxb5 is impossible, because of the fork on d6.} Bxc4 13. Bxc4 $16 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5,Ge3,Gf2][%cal Gb5c3] Here White has no problems and just enjoys a positional advantage.}) 11. f3 Be6 {[%csl Re3,Rf3] Compared to 10...Be6, the structure is not that great for White.} 12. Na5 $1 {[%csl Ba5] But, we still go for the same idea.} Qb6 13. Nc4 $1 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Rb6b5,Gc4d6] Key concept.} Bxc4 14. Bxc4 {The starting position of the critical line. Black is not out of danger yet, because White has the pair of bishops, so long term, if White will achieve, for example e4-Bg5, White is just better.} Be7 $1 {[%csl Be7][%cal Ge8h8] Best strategy for Black is to finish development as soon as possible.} (14... Bc5 $2 {[%csl Rc5] looks more ambitious, but in fact, it's just wrong.} 15. b4 $1 $16 {[%cal Rc5e3,Gb5d6] And Black is forced to go to e7, where b4 is just an useful inclusion.}) 15. O-O O-O 16. Qe2 $1 {[%csl Gb5,Gc4,Ge2] Useful move, to support all of the minor pieces.} Nc6 $1 {[%csl Bc6][%cal Gc6a5] The best defense, Black tries to justify the position in a concrete manner.} (16... Nbd7 $5 {possible, but a bit passive I would say.} 17. Kh1 $5 $14 {[%cal Ge3e4] Preparing e4, White is slightly better.}) 17. Ba2 $5 {[%csl Ga2] Good prophylactic move, so that Na5 doesn't come with tempo.} (17. Kh1 $6 {is too slow now:} Na5 $1 {[%csl Ga5,Rc4][%cal Ra5c4] Black's idea.} 18. Ba2 a6 19. Nc3 Nb3 $1 $11 {[%csl Ra1,Bb3,Rc1][%cal Gb3a1,Gb3c1] This is Black's point, position is equal.}) 17... Rac8 $1 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Gc8c1] The most useful.} (17... Na5 $2 {is nothing.} 18. b4 $1 $16 {[%cal Ra5c6] The knight has to go back.}) 18. Nc3 Na5 {[%csl Gc8][%cal Rb2b4] This is the point, but the beautiful stuff starts only now:} 19. Kh1 $1 {[%csl Gh1][%cal Ye3e4,Yg2g4] This is just an amazing prophylactic move, because it introduces many new ideas, like e4 or g4, followed by Rg1. Believe it or not, but Black has ONLY ONE good move in this position, otherwise he is seriously worse!} h6 $1 {[%csl Bh6] The best move according to the engine, but who will find it? Very difficult, in this concrete position to just give a move to the opponent, but the point is that h6 is a good prophylactic against g4-g5. And in fact, every White move is a small concession!} (19... Nb3 $2 {Black should understand that this fails tactically:} 20. Na4 $1 {[%csl Ba4] The point.} Nxc1 21. Nxb6 $1 {[%csl Bb6,Re2,Gh1][%cal Gc1e2] That's why 19.Kh1 was an amazing prophylactic.} Nxe2 22. Nxc8 Rxc8 23. Bb3 $1 $16 {[%csl Gb3,Re2][%cal Rc8c2,Gf1e1] To stop Rc2, the knight on e2 is lost, for some small compensation, but not full of course.}) (19... Bxa3 $2 {Greedy move.} 20. g4 $3 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gc3d5] g5 followed by Nd5 just wins the game.} h6 {Necessary.} 21. e4 $3 {[%csl Ge4,Gg4][%cal Gg4g5] Very nice refutation, and Black is close to being lost.} Bb4 (21... Rfd8 $1 {The best, but then we can go for the easy way:} 22. g5 $5 {White can play for an attack.} (22. Bxf7+ $5 {Simple.} Kxf7 23. Rxa3 $14 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gg4g5] White is slightly better at least.}) 22... hxg5 23. Rb1 Bb4 24. Bxg5 $40 {[%csl Rg8] The attack is still very dangerous.}) 22. g5 hxg5 23. Bxg5 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gf1g1] The attack is huge, for example:} Bxc3 24. bxc3 Rxc3 25. Rg1 Rfc8 26. Qg2 $1 {[%csl Rg8] White will most likely win immediately.} Ne8 27. Bd5 $40 {[%cal Gg2h3,Gg2g4,Ga1b1] The attack is only starting, and all of this for some irrelevant two pawns.}) (19... Rfd8 $6 {This is quite logical, but White can play positionally:} 20. e4 $1 {[%cal Gc1e3] To introduce Be3.} Nb3 $1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gb3c1,Gc1e2,Rc3a4] The knight has the d4 square now, so this move is possible.} 21. Be3 $1 Nd4 22. Qf2 $14 {[%cal Re7c5,Gb2b4,Gf1d1] Still, this is quite far away from equality for Black.}) 20. e4 {[%csl Ge4] The most logical positional try.} (20. g4 $5 {[%cal Gf8d8,Gb6a6] deserves attention, but Black has many moves.} Qa6 $5 $13 {[%csl Rg4] The endgame is more playable for Black now.}) 20... Nb3 $1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gb3c1,Gc1e2,Rc3a4] This move is strong now, because of the d4 square available for the knight.} 21. Be3 Nd4 22. Qd2 $5 {[%csl Gc3] To keep the c3 knight defended.} (22. Qf2 {And after any natural move, White is slightly better, but Black has:} Bxa3 $3 {[%csl Ba3] Fearless engine, just grabs a pawn, but of course, it's difficult to understand that it works.} 23. Na4 Qb5 $1 24. Bxd4 exd4 25. e5 $5 {[%csl Ge5] Good intermezzo, but engine claims equality after:} Be7 $3 $11 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Re5f6,Ge7f6] Okay, we can stop here, I guess the engine is right, but it's unlikely that this will ever happen.} (25... Nd5 $1 {Also possible.} 26. Bxd5 Qxd5 $11 {[%csl Ra4][%cal Ra1a3,Rb7b5,Yb2a3,Yd5b3] Whichever way White captures on a3, the knight on b5 is lost. Keep in mind that Black must calculate all of this when playing 22...Bxa3!})) (22. Bxd4 $5 {Extra option.} exd4 $1 (22... Qxd4 23. f4 $1 $40 {[%cal Re5f4,Ge4e5] Big attack.}) 23. Nd1 $14 {[%cal Gd1f2,Gf2d3] Positional advantage.}) 22... Rfd8 23. Nd5 {Just play solid.} (23. Qf2 $5 {[%csl Gf2] looks like we lost a tempo, but in fact, this way Bxa3 is less promising for Black.} Bxa3 $6 {is met with:} 24. Bxf7+ $1 $14 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Rg8f7,Ga1a3] And Black is forced to take with the king.}) 23... Nxd5 24. Bxd5 $14 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge3d4,Rb6a6] This is a slight advantage for White, even though engine is quite optimistic for Black. For a human, this is not pleasant at all. The bishop on d5 is a monster.} *

