{[%evp 0,23,27,19,13,-3,45,46,50,47,45,43,53,21,16,6,17,16,18,30,33,53,54,60,66,69]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 Bf5 $2 {Around 6000 games here, but it didn't stand well the test of time.} (2... Nf6 $6 {Around 20 years ago, if you ever saw this move, you would think that Black is just an amateur, but if you check who played this line, you can find a lot of 2700 players.} 3. cxd5 $1 {The best, other moves just transpose to theory.} g6 $5 {[%cal Rb1c3,Gf6d5] was played by GM Dubov, with the tricky idea to transpose to a Gruenfeld in case of Nc3.} (3... Nxd5 $6 {The most common, but not interesting.} 4. Nf3 {No need to rush with e4.} Bf5 5. Nbd2 $16 {[%cal Gg2g3,Ye2e4] e4 is a threat and if the knight goes to f6, you can just finish development.}) 4. Nf3 {I prefer this move, to play more standard.} (4. Qa4+ $5 {was played by Tabatabaei against Dubov, but I am not sure it is the best.} Bd7 5. Qb3 c6 $1 $44 {[%cal Rd5c6,Gb8c6] was an improvement, and Black should have some compensation for the missing pawn.} (5... b5 $2 {was a bad move played in the game.} 6. a4 $1 $16 {[%cal Rb5a4,Gb3b7] White has a close to winning advantage.})) 4... Bg7 (4... Nxd5 5. e4 $16 {[%csl Gb1,Gd4,Ge4][%cal Rd5c3] This is just a dream version of the Gruenfeld.}) 5. Qa4+ {We give this check now, and there are some differences:} c6 $1 {Black's best try.} (5... Bd7 {Not critical.} 6. Qb3 c6 7. Qxb7 cxd5 8. Ne5 $1 $16 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Rb8c6] The difference between having a knight on g1 and f3, we stop Nc6 and Black has no compensation for the pawn, and we can just finish development next.} (8. Qxa8 $2 {Don't fall for Black's trap.} Qb6 $1 $17 {[%csl Ra8][%cal Gd7c6,Ge8h8] Black is actually seriously better.})) 6. dxc6 {Other moves are also fine of course, but this looks critical.} Nxc6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. e4 $1 {[%csl Be4] The most principled, to grab the center.} (8. e3 $6 {is a bit too slow.} Bd7 9. Qb3 Re8 $1 $44 {[%cal Ge7e5] As shown in the email game Moreto-Ludwig, email 2021. Black has serious compensation for the pawn.}) 8... e5 $1 {[%csl Be5] The only logical reply, otherwise White is just a pawn up with a nice center.} 9. dxe5 Ng4 10. Be2 Ngxe5 {More or less forced.} 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. O-O {Still, I wouldn't say that White's advantage is too big, but a pawn is a pawn.} Nd4 13. Qd1 $5 $146 {Good prophylaxis move.} (13. Bc4 {also possible, but it was played in 2 email games, so maybe Black could have an idea.}) 13... Be6 14. f4 Nxe2+ 15. Qxe2 Bxc3 16. bxc3 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Rf6,Rg7,Rh6] The advantage is not big, but quite comfortable.}) 3. cxd5 $1 {[%csl Gd5] The best, using the fact that Black can't recapture with a pawn.} Bxb1 {The critical try.} (3... Nf6 {Black goes back to solid chess, but it's a bit too late.} 4. Nf3 Nxd5 5. Nbd2 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4] White is just better.}) 4. Rxb1 $1 {The principled way.} (4. Qa4+ {This leads only to a slightly better endgame.} c6 $1 {Black's idea.} 5. dxc6 Nxc6 6. Rxb1 Qxd4 7. Qxd4 Nxd4 8. e3 $14 {White has a 70% score here, so if you are not in the mood for concrete lines, this is a good solid option.}) 4... Qxd5 5. Nf3 $1 {White doesn't need to spend a tempo on a3.} Nf6 {Black should finish development somehow.} (5... Qxa2 $6 {quite risky.} 6. Bd2 $1 {[%csl Bd2] Important key move.} (6. Qc2 $2 {Don't start with this move immediately.} Nc6 $1 7. Bd2 e6 $36 {[%cal Gc6b4] Black is ready to jump to b4.}) 6... Nf6 (6... e6 $2 {too slow.} 7. e4 $18 {[%cal Rb8c6,Gf1b5] The evaluation is close to +4.}) 7. Qc2 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4] White is ready for e4, with a big advantage.}) 6. a3 $5 {Keeping the pawn is also fine.} (6. e3 $5 {We can continue to ignore the pawn.} Qxa2 7. Bd3 $16 {[%cal Gb2b4,Ge3e4] +1 evaluation at least.}) 6... Nc6 7. e3 e5 {Black's main try, but the endgame is miserable:} 8. dxe5 {[%csl Ge5,Rf6] To hit the knight with tempo.} Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Ng4 10. Ke2 Ngxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. f4 $1 $16 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gf1g2] g4-Bg2 next, serious advantage.} *

