{[%evp 0,39,27,-25,-6,-16,21,15,24,24,24,20,20,12,29,6,6,6,6,15,-3,-27,-22,-9,-2,-73,-62,-80,-75,-42,31,-34,-34,32,2,-1,2,44,29,54,47,26]} 1. c4 Nf6 2. d4 e5 {The Budapest Gambit. In the pre-computer era, it was quite popular, because Black plays very provocative, but in general, the structure is not so good.} 3. dxe5 Ng4 {The main line, White has a lot of good options, but for this course we will sugest something quite rare:} (3... Ne4 $6 {This was also considered in the past, but now this line is unplayable:} 4. a3 $1 {[%csl Ba3][%cal Rf8b4] Key move, to stop Bb4+.} (4. Nf3 $6 {is met with:} Bb4+ $1 $44 {And although it's not full compensation, Black can hope for some chances.}) 4... d6 {is probably Black's best.} (4... Nc6 $6 {Common, but a mistake.} 5. Nf3 d6 6. Qc2 $1 {[%csl Bc2][%cal Re4c5,Gb2b4] Important move, and Black is close to being lost.} Bf5 7. Nc3 $1 $18 {[%csl Bc3] Only move for an advantage, but an easy one.}) 5. Qc2 $1 {[%csl Bc2] Once again, precise move, and Black is in a bad situation.} Nc5 {The best.} (5... Bf5 $6 {is met with:} 6. Nc3 $1 $18 {[%cal Re4g3,Ge2e4] Typical refutation.}) 6. exd6 Bxd6 7. Nc3 $16 {[%cal Gg1f3,Ge2e4,Gb2b4] There is no compensation for the pawn. Just +1 evaluation, with easy development moves next.}) 4. e3 $5 {[%csl Ge3] Finish development, White doesn't even need to hold on to the pawn to be better.} Nxe5 5. f4 $1 {[%csl Re5,Bf4][%cal Re5g6,Re5c6] The key move and idea. The knight on e5 doesn't have a good retreating square.} Nec6 {[%cal Gf8c5,Gd7d6,Gb8d7] Probably the best square, but of course, it's quite slow, Black needs a lot of moves to finish development.} (5... Ng6 {Quite logical, and White can finish development and also be better thanks to the structure.} 6. h4 $1 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Gh4h5] The most ambitious and most principled. White plays to refute Black's system.} (6. Nc3 {also good enough.} Bc5 7. Nge2 $5 $146 {[%cal Ge2g3] Standard development.} O-O 8. Ng3 d6 9. Bd3 Re8 10. O-O {[%csl Rg6] Black's knight is just misplaced.} Bxe3+ 11. Bxe3 Rxe3 12. Qd2 Re8 13. f5 Ne5 14. f6 $18 {[%csl Rg8] Winning attack.}) 6... h5 {Black's only move, but now White can just finish development.} (6... Nxh4 $6 {Too optimistic.} 7. Nc3 Ng6 8. Nf3 {[%csl Gh1,Rh7][%cal Gh1h7] White is happy to give up the pawn, now we have the h-file for attack.} Nc6 9. Bd2 Bc5 10. Ng5 $16 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gd1h5] Black's position is very bad, close to lost.}) 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. Nc3 d6 9. Bd3 Be7 10. Bd2 {[%csl Re8] Black doesn't have a safe place for the king.} Nxh4 11. Nd5 $1 {[%csl Re7] White is close to having a winning advantage.} Nxf3+ 12. gxf3 $5 Be6 13. Bc3 $16 {[%csl Re8,Rg7] Black's best is to sacrifice g7 and try to long castle, but it's clear that White is seriously better.}) (5... Bb4+ $6 {Black can include this check, but I don't see much point to it.} 6. Bd2 Bxd2+ 7. Qxd2 Nec6 {The best square, White can develop in many ways, for example:} 8. Nc3 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Gc3d5] The knight for sure belongs on c3 and later d5.} d6 9. Nge2 $5 {[%csl Gf1][%cal Ge2g3] For now keeping the bishop flexible, it's not clear which square is the best.} Nd7 10. Ng3 O-O 11. Be2 {Position is new already.} Nc5 12. O-O $16 {[%csl Gc4,Rc7,Rd6][%cal Ge2f3,Gb2b3,Ge3e4,Ga1d1] White has a big positional advantage, any plan is good, Black has no counterplay.}) 6. Nc3 {We are not scared of Bb4.} (6. Ne2 $5 {Starting from this move also deserves attention.} Bc5 {Most logical.} (6... g6 {is met with:} 7. Bd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2c3] Deep idea, to immediately challenge the diagonal.} Bg7 8. Bc3 O-O 9. Bxg7 Kxg7 10. Nbc3 $16 {[%csl Gc3,Rg7][%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1,Gh2h4] This is always a great exchange for White, because it will be easier to start an attack.}) 7. Nbc3 O-O 8. Ng3 Re8 {[%csl Re3] Black's only idea, but White is not scared to give up the pawn:} 9. Bd3 $1 d6 {Black finishes development.} (9... Bxe3 $2 {Too greedy.} 10. Bxe3 Rxe3+ 11. Kf2 Re8 12. Nd5 $40 {[%csl Rg8] The attack is decisive.} d6 13. Qh5 g6 14. Qh6 $18 {[%cal Gg3h5] Nh5 next, Black can resign.}) 10. O-O Nd7 11. Nge4 $16 {[%csl Ge4] Evaluation is close to +1.}) 6... g6 $5 {[%cal Gf8g7] This is probably the most interesting way to develop for Black.} (6... Bc5 {The most logical.} 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Bd3 {White has a very big advantage, because the pieces are poorly placed for Black, and at any moment, White can start an attack, for example:} d6 9. O-O Nd7 10. a3 a5 11. Kh1 $5 {[%csl Gh1] Prophylactic, e4 could be an idea at some point.} Nf6 12. Qc2 {White has full control over the position.} Re8 13. Nd5 $1 {[%csl Rh7] To attack h7.} h6 14. Bd2 $16 {[%cal Gd5f6,Gd2c3] Serious advantage for White.}) (6... Bb4 $6 {Most common move.} 7. Nge2 $1 {[%csl Gc3][%cal Ge2c3] To develop and defend the c3 knight.} O-O 8. a3 Bxc3+ (8... Bc5 9. b4 $18 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gc3d5] Also very big advantage.}) 9. Nxc3 $16 {White had a very big advantage in Ivanisevic-Sevian, 2021.}) 7. b3 $5 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Gc1b2] I like challenging the diagonal.} Bg7 8. Bb2 d6 9. Qd2 $1 {[%csl Gd2] The best way to develop, the queen anyway belongs here.} (9. Be2 $5 {[%csl Ge2,Rg4] This is an interesting try, to control the g4 square.} O-O 10. Qd2 Na6 {To keep the bishop on c8 open.} (10... Nd7 {allows:} 11. Nh3 $5 {[%csl Rc8,Gh3][%cal Gh3f2] Cool development idea.} Nc5 12. Nf2 $14 {[%csl Gf2][%cal Ge1g1,Ga1d1,Ge2f3] The knight on f2 stays well, and finish development next with pressure.}) 11. Nd5 $5 {Concrete idea.} Nc5 12. Bxg7 Kxg7 13. b4 $1 {[%csl Bb4] Key move.} Ne4 14. Qb2+ f6 15. Bd3 {[%csl Re4] The knight is in trouble.} Re8 16. Qc2 $1 $16 {[%cal Rc8f5,Gg2g4] White is seriously better.}) (9. Nge2 $6 {is not so precise to start this way.} Bg4 $1 {[%csl Bg4] The bishop gets this nice square.} 10. Qd2 Nd7 11. Ng3 Qh4 $1 $132 {[%cal Rh2h3] To stop h3, Black has a more or less playable position.}) 9... O-O {The most logical.} (9... Bg4 $6 {runs into:} 10. Nd5 $1 {[%cal Gd2b2] The point of Qd2.} O-O 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. Be2 $5 {[%cal Gd2c3] You can include a check on c3 anytime.} Bxe2 13. Nxe2 $16 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Ge1g1,Ge2g3,Ge3e4,Gf4f5] White is doing simply fanastic.}) 10. Nge2 Bg4 {The critical idea.} (10... Nd7 11. Ng3 Nc5 12. Be2 $16 {[%csl Rc6,Ge3,Gf4][%cal Ge1g1] White has a very flexible development, and the pawns e3 and f4 are perfectly placed against the knight on c6.}) 11. Ng3 Nd7 {Black finishes development, and the line is critical:} (11... Qh4 12. Nd5 $1 $16 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Ge8c8] Black's king is on g8, so there is no long castle available.}) 12. Bd3 Nc5 13. Bb1 $1 {[%csl Gb1] The best square, the bishop is safe here.} (13. Bc2 $6 {runs into:} Nb4 $1 $132 {[%cal Gd6d5] With counterplay.}) 13... Nb4 14. O-O $1 {[%cal Gf4f5,Gh2h3] f5, followed by h3 is a very serious threat.} d5 {Black starts their counterplay.} 15. cxd5 Nxd5 16. Nxd5 Bxb2 17. Qxb2 Qxd5 {Black did some progress, at least now it's not absolutely bad:} 18. b4 $5 {[%csl Gb4][%cal Gb1e4] Good move to get control of the e4 square.} Na4 19. Qa3 Bd7 20. Bc2 $14 {[%cal Rd7c6,Gc2e4] White however should still be better.} *

