1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 b6 3. Nc3 Bb7 4. Qc2 {[%cal Ge2e4] White wants to play e2-e4.} d5 {This is Black's only playable idea, to stop e4.} (4... g6 {Other moves except 4...d5 are not interesting.} 5. e4 d6 6. Nf3 Bg7 7. Be2 O-O {Only thing to know is to not castle too early:} 8. Be3 {[%csl Ye3][%cal Gf3d2,Gg2g4] Good developing move, the point is that sometimes White is planning to stop kingside counterplay with g2-g4.} (8. O-O $6 {is premature.} e5 9. d5 a5 $132 {[%cal Gb7c8,Gb8a6] Black has a playable position.}) 8... e5 (8... Nbd7 {Black can also wait with ...e7-e5.} 9. h3 {Useful move.} e5 10. d5 {[%cal Gg2g4] g4 is the idea, after which White has a serious advantage.} Nh5 11. g3 {[%cal Rh5f4,Rf7f5,Gf3g5,Gg5e6] To stop Nf4.} h6 12. O-O-O f5 13. Nh4 $16 {[%csl Rf5,Rg6] Black is losing material most likely.}) 9. d5 a5 10. Nd2 Na6 (10... Bc8 11. h3 $16 {[%csl Ge1,Gg4][%cal Gg2g4] g4 next, White has a big advantage.}) 11. g4 $14 {[%csl Gg4] Positional idea, White is better.}) (4... e6 $2 {This leads to a very bad version of the Nimzo for Black.} 5. e4 Bb4 6. Bd3 $16 {White has a very big advantage.}) 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. e4 {Logical and straightforward.} (6. Bd2 {I used to play this lazy move, with the point to be able to capture on c3 with the bishop, but it leads to nothing.} e6 7. e4 (7. Nf3 {also doesn't improve the situation.} Nb4 8. Qa4+ Qd7 $11 {[%cal Gc7c5] Black is ready to trade queens or to play c5.}) 7... Nb4 $1 {[%csl Gb4] is a strong move, and Black is doing fine.} (7... Nxc3 8. Bxc3 $14 {This is the point of 6.Bd2.}) 8. Qa4+ Qd7 9. Qxd7+ Nxd7 10. O-O-O c5 $11 {Absolutely fine endgame for Black.}) 6... Nxc3 {Necessary.} (6... Nb4 $4 {This doesn't work now, because the knight is unprotected.} 7. Qa4+ $18 {[%csl Rb4,Re7] White wins.}) 7. bxc3 {The starting position, Black has two possible lines: the positional 7...e6 and the concrete 7...e5.} e5 $5 {The most interesting move, in my opinion. It was played in the very recent game Esipenko-Rapport, Rostov 2025.} (7... e6 {Normal move, Black wants to just finish development.} 8. Nf3 Be7 $1 {The best move, not commiting to anything for now.} (8... Nd7 $2 {Bad move.} 9. Bd3 Be7 {This can be reached through the 8...Be7 move order as well.} (9... c5 {is now met with} 10. d5 $1 {[%csl Gd5] Important move, to open the central files.} exd5 11. exd5 Bxd5 12. O-O {White is a pawn down, but Black's situation is critical:} Be7 13. Rd1 {[%csl Gd1,Rd5][%cal Gd1d5] Concrete problems with the pin.} Bxf3 14. gxf3 {[%csl Rd7,Rd8][%cal Gd3f5] Another pin.} Qc7 15. Qa4 {[%csl Rd7] Game over for Black.} O-O-O 16. Bf5 $18 {[%csl Rd7][%cal Gd1d7,Gc1f4,Ga1d1] No defence against concrete tactics.}) 10. O-O O-O (10... c5 {is as usually met with} 11. d5 $16 {[%csl Rd7] Big positional advantage.}) 11. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Gf4] Strong move and the most active square for the bishop.} c5 12. d5 exd5 13. exd5 {[%csl Gf4,Rh7][%cal Gd3h7,Gd5d6] White has two threats.} Nf6 14. c4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd5] White has a positional advantage, for exmaple:} b5 15. Rab1 {[%csl Rb7] Pin.} bxc4 16. Bxc4 Bxd5 17. Rbd1 $1 {White is winning thanks to the pin.} (17. Rfd1 $2 Be4 $13 {[%csl Rb1][%cal Ge4c2,Gc2b1] The rook on b1 is hanging in some lines.}) 17... Be4 18. Bxf7+ {Tactic.} Kxf7 (18... Kh8 19. Qc4 $18 {[%csl Gd1,Gf1]}) 19. Ng5+ $1 $18 {[%cal Gg5e4]}) (8... c5 $2 {[%csl Rc5] Immediately is premature.} 9. Bb5+ $1 {[%csl Gb5] Annoying check, and it disrupts Black's coordination.} Bc6 {Necessary.} (9... Nd7 $4 {just loses.} 10. Ne5 $18 {[%csl Rd7] Huge problems with the knight.}) 10. Bd3 {[%csl Rc6,Gd3] The bishop is seriously misplaced on c6.} cxd4 11. cxd4 Bb4+ 12. Kf1 $1 {[%csl Gf1] The king is good on f1.} O-O 13. h4 $16 {[%csl Rb4,Rc6,Rg8,Gh4][%cal Gh1h3] Black's pieces are mislaced, White can just go for an attack (+1.50 advantage).}) 9. Bd3 c5 $1 {The only good move, and the best Black can achieve.} (9... O-O $2 {[%csl Rg8] This is a mistake.} 10. e5 $1 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Gd3h7] Open the diagonal, White has a winning position.} h6 11. h4 $18 {[%csl Rc2,Rd3,Rh6][%cal Gh1h3,Gh3g3,Gc1h6] Very straightforward attack, +2 something evaluation.}) (9... Nd7 {see under 8...Nd7.}) 10. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Gf4] The only move that allows White to fight for a big advantage.} (10. O-O $6 {leads to nothing special.} cxd4 11. cxd4 O-O 12. Bb2 Nd7 $132 {[%csl Ob2,Oe7,Gf4][%cal Ga8c8,Gd8c7,Gc7f4] White is slightly slightly better, but it's a typical playable Semi-Tarrasch position.}) 10... cxd4 {The critical move.} (10... O-O 11. d5 $1 {Typical sacrifice.} exd5 12. exd5 Qxd5 {Critical move.} 13. O-O {[%csl Rh7] White has huge compensation, for example:} Qh5 {[%csl Rf3,Yh7][%cal Yb7f3] Logical move, to protect h7 and attack f3.} 14. Rae1 $1 {[%csl Re7][%cal Ge1e7] Good intermediate move.} Bf6 15. Re3 {[%cal Gf3e5,Ge3h3] The initiative is overwhelming, White's pieces are well coordinated:} Nc6 16. Nd2 {[%cal Ge3h3] Tempo.} g6 17. Ne4 {Improve the knight with tempo.} Bg7 18. Nd6 $16 {[%csl Gd6] Big advantage for White.}) 11. Bb5+ $1 $146 {[%cal Rb8c6] Important intermezzo, because it doesn't allow Black to play ...Nc6.} Bc6 {Necessary move.} (11... Nc6 $4 {loses the knight after} 12. Nxd4 $18 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gc2a4] Qa4 next and the knight will not survive.}) (11... Nd7 $4 12. Ne5 $18 {Problems with the pin.}) 12. Nxd4 $1 {[%csl Rc7,Gd4,Rd6,Gf4][%cal Gd4b5] Now we can see the point of 10.Bf4, it supports the knight jumps to c7 or d6.} Bd7 {The best.} (12... Bxb5 $2 13. Nxb5 {[%csl Gc7,Gf4][%cal Gb5c7] Nc7+ is a threat.} Na6 14. Rd1 $1 {We play for the d6 square.} Qc8 15. Bd6 $16 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Re8g8,Re7d6,Rc8c4,Ga2a4] Black can't castle, nor capture on d6, White is just better.}) 13. O-O O-O 14. Rfd1 Qe8 15. a4 {[%cal Rd7b5,Ga4b5] Good move, to support the bishop on b5.} Bc5 16. Bg3 Bxb5 {It is up to White whether to sacrifice the pawn or not.} (16... Bxd4 17. Bxd7 $1 {Good intermezzo, and Black can't win material.} Bxf2+ 18. Qxf2 Nxd7 19. Bd6 $16 {[%csl Rf8] The rook is trapped.}) 17. axb5 $5 {Actually, a very nice pawn sacrifice.} (17. Nxb5 {You can also play just for a positional advatange.} Na6 18. Rd2 $14 {[%csl Ra6,Ra7] Black has clumsy pieces.}) 17... Bxd4 18. cxd4 Qxb5 19. d5 $36 {White has a huge initiative thanks to the active pieces.}) 8. Nf3 exd4 {This is Black's idea, of course.} (8... Nd7 $2 {Too slow.} 9. Bc4 {White will just achieve excellent play.} Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Rd1 $16 {[%csl Gc3,Gc4,Gd4,Ge4] +1.50 evaluation.}) 9. Bb5+ $1 {This is our typical idea, to provoke disruption in Black's development.} (9. cxd4 $2 {is a mistake, because it allows} Bb4+ $1 {[%csl Gb4] And White doesn't have a satisfactory response.} 10. Bd2 Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 Bxe4 $36 {At maximum, White can equalize with accurate play.}) 9... Nd7 $1 {The key response for Black.} (9... c6 {Most common move.} 10. Bc4 {[%csl Rb7,Gc4,Rc6] This inclusion was definitely in White's favor.} b5 (10... dxc3 $2 11. Ng5 $18 {[%csl Rf7] Black can resign.}) 11. Be2 $1 {Best retreating square.} (11. Bb3 $2 c5 $36 {[%csl Rb3][%cal Gc5c4] Black wants to target the bishop.}) 11... dxc3 {was played in the game Pilgaard-Grachev, La Roda 2019.} 12. Qxc3 {[%csl Rf8] Black has difficulties developing the kingside.} Nd7 13. O-O b4 14. Qb2 $5 $146 {[%csl Gb2][%cal Rf8e7] Clear improvement over the game, the queen is more active on this diagonal.} Be7 {Necessary move.} 15. Rd1 {[%csl Rd7] To pin the knight.} O-O (15... Bf6 $2 {just loses to simple} 16. e5 $1 Be7 17. e6 $1 $18 {[%csl Rd7] Easy win.}) 16. Ne5 {White will win material.} Bf6 17. Rxd7 Qe8 18. Rxb7 Bxe5 19. Qb1 Bxa1 20. Qxa1 Qxe4 21. Be3 $16 {[%csl Rb4,Rc6,Ge2,Ge3] The bishops are fantastic, and the pawns will most likely fall.}) 10. Ne5 $1 {The most critical move, and it was played by Esipenko.} (10. cxd4 {was played in Schitco-Grachev, 2020.} Bb4+ $11 {Black is fine here.}) (10. O-O {was played in Ter Sahakyan-Bortnyk, 2023.} a6 $1 {Good move.} 11. Bc4 $5 $146 {White seems to have great compensation, but Black has a strong idea:} d3 $1 {Good intermezzo.} 12. Qxd3 b5 $1 {[%csl Rc4] And Black will win the pair of bishops.} 13. Bd5 {To at least provoke c6, but it doens't change much.} (13. Bb3 $6 Nc5 $36 {[%csl Rb3]}) 13... c6 14. Bb3 Nc5 $1 {White can fight for some slight advantage, but slowly Black should equalize:} 15. Qe2 Nxb3 16. axb3 Be7 17. Nd4 $14 {[%cal Ge2f3,Gd4f5] Playable position though, if you like, you can play it.}) 10... c6 {Only move.} 11. Nxc6 {Esipenko went for the maximum.} (11. Bxc6 {White will win material, but Black will play for nice compensation:} Bxc6 12. Nxc6 Qc7 13. Nxd4 Rc8 {Very natural developing moves.} 14. O-O {Better to castle.} (14. Bb2 Bc5 $44 {Almost full compensation.}) 14... Qxc3 15. Qxc3 Rxc3 16. Bb2 {White plays for the development advantage.} Rc7 17. Rac1 Nc5 18. Rfd1 $14 {Black can equalize if they play like an engine, but it's definitely unpleasant.}) 11... Bxc6 12. Bxc6 Rc8 13. cxd4 Bb4+ 14. Ke2 $1 {[%csl Ge2][%cal Gh1d1] Good move, to bring also the rook into the game.} Qc7 (14... O-O $2 {This is a big mistake.} 15. Qa4 $1 {[%csl Ga4,Rb4,Rd7] Double attack.} Nb8 16. Bd5 $18 {+2 evaluation.}) 15. a3 $1 $146 {[%csl Ga3,Rb4] This is my recommendation, and improvement over the game.} (15. d5 {is how the game continued, but it was not so easy to break through after:} O-O 16. Rb1 Bd6 17. Bb2 Nb8 {Black has nice play.} 18. Qc3 f6 19. Rhc1 Nxc6 20. Qxc6 Qe7 21. Qa4 f5 $11 {In the end, it finished in a draw, Black has full compensation.}) 15... Bd6 16. Bxd7+ Qxd7 17. Qd3 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gc8c3] This is the point of 15.a3, there is no Rc3 tempo now.} Qg4+ {Critical move.} (17... O-O 18. h3 $16 {[%csl Gh3][%cal Rd7g4,Gh1d1,Ge2f1] White just play with an extra pawn, +1 position.}) 18. Kf1 $1 {The best.} (18. Qf3 $6 {allows Black to slowly equalize after} Rc2+ $1 19. Bd2 Qxf3+ 20. gxf3 Bf4 21. Rhd1 Kd7 $11 {It should end in a draw.}) 18... O-O 19. Be3 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh1h3] White has an extra pawn, and it's really difficult to hold this with Black.} Qg6 $1 {The best, already difficult to find.} (19... Rfe8 20. f3 $16 {[%cal Gf1f2,Gh1c1] Just Kf2-Rc1 next.}) 20. g3 $14 {Still, the evaluation is +0.50 and over the board it is not easy to prove Black's compensation, the only problem White has in the position is the king on f1, but with all pieces in the game, it is just a technical position (extra pawn+nice center). With this, we finish our journey and I wish you good luck in your games, see you soon!} *

