{[%evp 0,35,32,27,24,-3,29,29,26,28,33,8,26,26,26,24,59,69,53,49,51,38,38,38,38,4,4,11,10,13,-10,-13,-12,-12,-7,2,39,27]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 d6 3. Nc3 Nbd7 {[%cal Ge7e5,Gf8e7,Ge8g8] The Old Indian Defense. Black aims to play e5 and develop the bishop to e7.} (3... g6 {transposes to the Classical KID.} 4. g3 Bg7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Nf3 {This is our recommended setup.}) (3... e5 4. Nf3 e4 {This is Black's critical try.} (4... Nbd7 {transposes to the main line.}) (4... exd4 {Not challenging.} 5. Nxd4 g6 6. e4 $14 {Just slightly better for White in many ways.}) 5. Ng5 $1 {[%csl Bg5] This is the most critical option.} (5. Nd2 {In my game against GM Dimitrov, I was not prepared and chose this safe option.} Bf5 6. e3 c6 7. Be2 d5 {Black is playing a strange version of the French with colors reversed, but White has a lot of useful extra tempi:} 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Qb3 Qd7 10. g4 $1 {[%csl Bg4] I found a nice tactical idea.} Be6 (10... Bxg4 $2 {Taking is bad.} 11. Bxg4 Nxg4 12. Nxd5 $16 {[%csl Gd5,Rg4] The d5 pawn is more important than the g4 one.}) 11. g5 Ng8 12. Ndxe4 $5 {[%csl Be4] This was the point of my play, and Black had to accept the challenge.} Nc6 $2 {My opponent just gave me the pawn for free, and of course, I covnerted the extra pawn.} (12... dxe4 $1 $146 {was necessary.} 13. d5 Bf5 14. Bb5 Nc6 $1 {looks dangerous for Black, but in reality it's equal.} 15. dxc6 bxc6 16. Ba4 Bd6 $11 {[%csl Rg5][%cal Gg8e7,Ge8h8,Gh8g8] The structure is vulnerable, but it should be a balanced position, White is a bit overextended.}) 13. Ng3 a6 14. Bd2 b5 15. f4 g6 16. h4 h5 17. Nd1 {[%cal Gd1f2,Gf2d3] The knight goes to d3, and I won an easy morning round.} Nge7 18. Nf2 Nf5 19. Nxf5 Bxf5 20. Rc1 $18 {Basso-Dimitrov, 1-0, Cattolica Primavera op 2022.}) 5... Bf5 (5... Qe7 6. f3 $5 {[%csl Gf3] I like this rare option, to clarify the central situation immediately.} (6. Qc2 {The main line, but it leads to a very complicated game:} Nc6 $13 {You can find a lot of games of GM Rakhmanov, who actually scored extremely well from the Black side.}) 6... exf3 7. Nxf3 {White has a positional advantage.} g6 8. e4 $1 {[%csl Be4] Key idea.} Bg7 (8... Nxe4 $4 {fails to:} 9. Nd5 $1 $18 {[%csl Rc7,Gd5,Re7][%cal Re7d8,Gd1e2] The point, and Black is on the verge of collapse.}) 9. Bd3 O-O 10. O-O $16 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4] Fantastic center and pieces, White is much better.}) 6. g4 $1 {[%csl Bg4] Typical idea.} Bxg4 (6... Nxg4 7. Ngxe4 $16 {[%cal Ge4g3] The e pawn is more important than the g pawn.}) 7. Bg2 $5 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Gg5e4] White wants to be able to recapture with the bishop at the end.} Be7 (7... Nc6 8. Ngxe4 Nxe4 9. Bxe4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gh1g1] The point, White is better.}) 8. Ngxe4 Nxe4 9. Bxe4 c6 10. Rg1 $16 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge2] Strong center and open g-file for the rook, that's why the ...e4 try is quite double edged for Black.}) (3... Bf5 {[%cal Re2e4] This is a possible sideline, Black aims to stop e4.} 4. Nf3 g6 {Black's main try.} (4... Nbd7 $6 {[%cal Ge7e5] Black is not in time to push e5.} 5. Nh4 $1 {[%csl Rf5] We manage to capture the pair of bishops.} Bg6 6. Nxg6 hxg6 7. g3 $16 {[%csl Gf1][%cal Gf1g2] Better position for White, the g2 bishop will be a monster.}) 5. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Bb3] This is an important inclusion.} (5. h3 $6 {[%cal Gg2g4] with idea g4 is a bit slow.} Ne4 $1 $132 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Rg2g4,Ge4c3] Black is able to create some play.}) 5... b6 {The main move.} (5... Qc8 {Logical, but now we go for our main idea.} 6. h3 $1 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gg2g4] g4 is a big threat.} Bg7 (6... h5 {[%cal Rg2g4,Gf3g5] stops g4, but it's too risky.} 7. Ng5 $1 $16 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gc4c5,Ge2e4] Too many threats.}) (6... Ne4 7. g4 $1 {[%csl Gb3,Gg4] The point is that now Nxc3 doesn't come with tempo:} Nxc3 8. gxf5 $1 {Intermezzo.} Ne4 9. fxg6 hxg6 10. h4 $1 $16 {[%cal Gf1h3] Big positional advantage for White.}) 7. g4 Bd7 8. e4 {[%csl Gc4,Gd4,Ge4] White captures all the center.} O-O 9. Bg2 $16 {White is better with any normal move.} (9. e5 $5) (9. Be2 $5)) 6. h3 $1 {[%cal Gg2g4] We go for the expansion plan.} Bg7 {The best, and it was played by Caruana.} (6... Ne4 $2 7. g4 $1 {[%csl Gb3,Rd1][%cal Re4c3] And once again thanks to the inclusion, White is in time to capture on f5.} Nxc3 8. gxf5 $18 {[%csl Ra6,Rb7,Rc6][%cal Gf1g2] This is even a worse version, because look at the light squares.}) 7. g4 Bc8 8. Bg2 Bb7 9. Qc2 $1 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4] This is how the game Eljanov-Caruana, 2024, continued. White is better, capturing the maximum space and all the center after e2-e4.}) 4. Nf3 {I recommend to play without the move e2-e4.} (4. e4 {The main move, but it doesn't fit well with our repertoire.} e5 5. Nf3 Be7 {The Classical Old Indian, where you need to have a lot of experience.} (5... g6 $5 {[%csl Ge4,Gg6] Black can go for a King's Indian now, it is unlikely, but we don't play the classical setup with e4.} 6. Be2 {It is only one line, but it is a tricky variation, that requires good knowledge and experience.})) 4... e5 5. Bg5 $5 {Throughout the years I had analyzed deeply this system, that keeps the game independent.} Be7 {The main line by far.} (5... h6 {Rare line, but it exists as well.} 6. Bh4 g5 7. Bg3 Nh5 $5 {[%csl Gh5][%cal Gh5g3] This is Black's idea, to hunt down the bishop.} 8. e3 Bg7 9. Qc2 $5 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Ge1c1,Ge1g1] For now, this is the most flexible way to develop, not revealing yet which side we are going to castle.} O-O 10. Rd1 $1 $146 {[%csl Gd1][%cal Gd1d8] I think this is a good option, to put pressure on the queen.} (10. O-O-O $6 {[%cal Rh5g3] If Nxg3 was played, I would somewhat understand 0-0-0, but in this case it seems a bit premature.} Re8 $132 {The game is quite complex.}) 10... Re8 11. Be2 {White can finish development.} Nxg3 12. hxg3 c6 13. O-O Qc7 {With a pawn on g6, Black would be fine, but thanks to the weakness, White is slightly better:} 14. dxe5 $5 {[%csl Be5] Instructive way to seize the advantage, Black doesn't have a satisfactory response:} dxe5 (14... Nxe5 15. Rd2 $14 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Gf1d1] Just double the rooks and put pressure on the weak d6 pawn.}) 15. Ne4 $1 $14 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gg3g4,Ge4g3,Oe4d6] White can fight for the f5 square, Black is a bit behind in development as well.}) 6. e3 O-O (6... c6 {was played against me by GM David Alberto.} 7. Bd3 h6 8. Bh4 exd4 {This is a standard reaction from Black, to liberate the pieces a bit.} 9. Nxd4 Ne5 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O Bd7 12. Bg3 $14 {I was slightly better for free, +0.60 advantage. Basso-David, ITA-ch Padova 2019.}) 7. Bd3 $5 {[%csl Od1,Cd3] This is my idea, for the moment we keep the queen on d1, and the reason is that we are indirectly fighting against the ...Nh5 ideas.} (7. Qc2 $6 {[%csl Rc2] In this case, this move is a bit premature, and the reason is quite instructive:} c6 8. Bd3 h6 9. Bh4 Re8 {Natural moves so far.} 10. O-O Nh5 $1 {[%csl Gh4,Bh5] Key resource, to get rid of the active bishop.} 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 $132 {The position is playable, but all in all, Black should be happy with the opening outcome.}) 7... c6 {Main move.} (7... h6 8. Bh4 exd4 {Logical try.} (8... e4 $2 {Don't worry, you are not losing a piece:} 9. Bxf6 $1 $16 {[%csl Gf6] Intermezzo and it is White who wins material.}) 9. Nxd4 Nc5 10. Bc2 $14 {Normal move, this structure is usually very pleasant for White and unpleasant for Black (due to lack of counterplay).} (10. O-O $5 {This is possible as well, since we are not afraid to give up the light squares bishop.} Nxd3 11. Qxd3 $14 {[%csl Rc7,Rd6] Eventually, the weakness of the Black structure will be a real pain to deal with.})) 8. O-O Re8 {Let's finally understand the point of keeping the queen on d1:} (8... Qc7 {was played against me by FM Luciani.} 9. h3 $5 {[%csl Gh3][%cal Gg5h4,Gh4g3,Gg3h2] I went for this useful prophylactic move.} Re8 10. Bh4 {I gave my opponent a chance to liberate his position a bit:} (10. Re1 $1 $16 {[%csl Ge1] was a serious improvement for a significant advantage.}) 10... Bf8 (10... e4 $1 {[%csl Be4] Still, it doesn't equalize, just it becomes easier to play with Black.} 11. Bxf6 exf3 12. Bxe7 fxg2 $1 {[%csl Rf1][%cal Rg2f1] Key intermezzo.} 13. Kxg2 Rxe7 14. Qh5 Nf6 15. Qh4 $14 {However, still White is slightly better.}) 11. Qc2 $16 {My opponent didn't see it, and I had a very comfortable advantage, very good and healthy setup. Basso-Luciani, 1-0, Bassano del Grappa op 2020.}) 9. Re1 $1 {[%csl Be1] Only 2 games out of 20, but this is the most useful move in the position since it is eventually also a good prophylaxis against ...e5-e4 tricks.} h6 10. Bh4 Nh5 {[%csl Rc2,Gd1] Compared to having a queen on c2, White has a nice resource available:} 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Nxe5 $1 {[%csl Bd1,Rh5][%cal Gd1h5] This is the main point, the knight on h5 is hanging.} dxe5 $1 {The best out of the 2 recaptures.} (12... Nxe5 $6 {[%cal Ge5d3] Attacks d3, so we must recapture.} 13. dxe5 Qxe5 14. f4 $1 {[%csl Re5,Rh5] Great tempo.} Qa5 15. Ne4 $1 {[%cal Ge4d6,Gb2b4] b4 is a huge threat.} Nf6 {The best for the engine, but it's a sad move to play.} (15... Rd8 $4 {loses a piece.} 16. b4 $1 $18 {[%csl Ra5,Gd1,Rh5] Distracting the queen, game over.}) 16. Nxf6+ gxf6 17. Kh1 $16 {[%csl Rf6,Rf7,Rh6] Black is just much worse.}) 13. Qxh5 exd4 14. exd4 $1 {We enter this seemingly unclear position:} Qxe1+ 15. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 16. Bf1 Nf6 17. Qf3 Bd7 18. Qf4 $1 $14 {[%csl Bf4][%cal Gf2f3,Gg1f2,Gf4c7,Gg2g4,Gh2h4,Gg4g5] The engine shows +0.60, so it is a very good advantage, the reason is simple, White has very simple ways to improve the position, starting with f3-Kf2 to get rid of the pin, and next White can expand on the kingside.} *

