{[%evp 0,75,17,17,17,-3,35,37,32,17,12,10,29,30,31,42,39,18,35,53,77,101,59,109,32,109,28,35,35,41,41,41,70,72,111,93,59,74,116,81,49,66,66,93,31,57,31,36,23,93,77,58,57,51,46,58,43,5,68,35,0,0,-17,67,62,63,65,65,59,78,67,67,67,64,73,80,73,77]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. g3 O-O 5. Bg2 d6 6. Nc3 Bd7 $5 7. O-O Re8 {[%cal Ge7e5] This system was introduced in practice by Jorden Van Foreest. Black's idea is to play e5.} 8. Qb3 {This is White's most principled continuation.} (8. e4 {This is White's most natural move, but after} e5 9. d5 (9. h3 Nc6 10. d5 Nd4 $1 $13 {[%csl Ge8] This idea is possible because of the move Re8.}) 9... a5 $132 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gb8a6] If we compare it to the 6...Nc6 7.00 e5 8.d5 Nb8 variation, here Black did not lose time with the knight.}) (8. Bf4 {White stops e5.} Qc8 {[%cal Gf6g4,Ge7e5] Black's idea is Bh3, or Ng4-e5.} 9. Qd2 (9. Re1 Ng4 $1 $146 10. h3 e5 $13 {very unclear.}) 9... Bh3 (9... Ng4 $2 {not so strong now, because after} 10. h3 e5 11. hxg4 exf4 {White can take on f4 with the queen} 12. Qxf4 $16) 10. e4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Nbd7 12. Bg5 $5 $146 (12. e5 Nh5 $1 $13 {Baenziger-Berkes, 2023.}) 12... a6 $5 $14 {[%cal Gb7b5] White can play, but Black has different ideas.}) (8. b4 $5 $146 {You can also go for something complitely new if you wish, for example:} Qc8 (8... Nc6 9. a3 e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Bg5 $14) (8... e5 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Bg5 $14) 9. Bg5 $14) 8... Nc6 $1 {The critical continuation.} (8... Qc8 $2 {Logical, but White has} 9. Ne5 $1 $16 {[%csl Gb7,Yd7][%cal Gg2b7,Ye5d7] The b7 pawn is hanging, and after Black will defend it, White will capture on d7 and will be better thanks to the pair of bishops.}) (8... b6 {[%csl Ga8][%cal Gg2a8] Black will have problems on the long diagonal, but also on the c6 square.} 9. Qc2 $5 $146 {The queen is not useful anymore on b3.} Nc6 {Logical move.} 10. d5 Nb4 11. Qd1 {If Black would have the same position, but with the pawn on b7, he would be fine, but now after} c6 12. Nd4 $16 {[%csl Gc6] After the exchange on d5 Black will have problems on the c6 square.}) 9. Qxb7 Na5 10. Qa6 $5 $146 {We will see now that Black will need to play a very long series of only moves.} (10. Qb4 c5 {Transposes to what we will see in the main line, but I prefer starting with 10.Qa6, so that Black is forced to find a few other precise moves.}) 10... c5 11. dxc5 Bc8 $1 {Only move.} 12. Qb5 Bd7 $1 {Only move. Of course, White can repeat, but better to play for more:} 13. Qb4 Rb8 14. Qa3 Nxc4 15. Qa6 $1 d5 16. Rd1 {Everything was forced till this point.} Qc8 $1 (16... Nxb2 $2 17. Bxb2 Rxb2 18. Ne5 $1 $16) (16... e6 $6 {Black defends the d5 pawn, but after} 17. b3 {[%csl Yc4] There are some problems with the knight. The critical line is} Ne4 18. Nxe4 Bxa1 19. Bf4 $1 Qc8 20. Qxc8 Rbxc8 21. bxc4 dxe4 22. Ng5 e5 23. Rxd7 exf4 24. Nxf7 $16) 17. Qxc8 Rbxc8 $1 (17... Rexc8 $4 {natural, but bad recapture.} 18. b3 Ne4 19. Nxd5 $18 {[%csl Ge7][%cal Gd5e7] White has Nxe7+ ideas.}) 18. b3 Ne4 $1 {Necessary.} 19. Nxe4 Bxa1 20. Neg5 {We are already 10 moves ahead of our novelty, but this position is really important, and we cannot stop yet.} h6 $1 (20... Na5 $6 21. Bd2 Bg7 22. Bxa5 Rxc5 23. Bb4 $16) (20... Ne5 $4 21. Nxe5 Bxe5 22. Rxd5 $18) 21. Nh3 (21. bxc4 $5 {Also deserves attention.} Ba4 22. Rf1 hxg5 23. cxd5 g4 $1 {Only move for Black not to get a worse position.} 24. Ng5 Bd4 25. c6 e6 $13) 21... Ne5 (21... g5 $5 {Also possible, according to the engine.} 22. bxc4 Ba4 23. Rf1 dxc4 24. Be3 Bb2 25. Nd2 c3 26. Nc4 Rb8 27. c6 $36) 22. Nxe5 Bxe5 23. Rxd5 {Now, engine's evaluation is 0.00, but only because of the following incredible variation:} Rcd8 24. Rxe5 Bc8 $3 {Only move.} 25. Bd5 Bxh3 26. b4 {Looks great for White, but with only moves Black can hold:} Rd7 27. c6 Rd6 28. b5 Red8 29. e4 Kf8 $3 {Only defense.} 30. Bxh6+ Ke8 31. Be3 f6 $1 32. Bxa7 $3 fxe5 33. b6 e6 $1 {Again, only move.} 34. b7 exd5 35. c7 dxe4 36. cxd8=Q+ (36. f3 $5 {You can have fun investigating this move by yourself.}) 36... Rxd8 37. b8=Q Rxb8 38. Bxb8 $11 {With a draw. As we have seen, against the modern hybrid Bd7+Re8, you can choose to play a slightly better game with 8.Bf4 or 8.b4!?N, or if to test your opponent with the principled 8.Qb3, where if Black wants to equalize, he then needs to remember an ocean of only moves starting from 8...Nc6! I hope that you enjoyed the beautiful forced variation that we have seen!} *

