{[%evp 0,47,31,20,19,-3,4,4,19,9,22,22,12,28,21,10,52,22,18,21,17,12,5,7,10,20,15,4,8,8,12,4,1,15,16,32,43,47,60,64,59,64,60,55,55,58,46,43,85,73]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 a6 4. Bg5 $5 {This is my offer against the sideline 3...a6. It is a serious move, that's why I recommend something tricky and practical, very much in the spirit of the repertoire.} Be7 5. Bxe7 Qxe7 {The critical response.} (5... Nxe7 {[%csl Ye7] It is tried from time to time, but it's not challenging, the knight belongs to f6.} 6. Nbd2 O-O 7. g3 {[%csl Re7] White has a very comfortable setup, and it's not clear what the knight is doing on e7.} Nd7 8. Bg2 c5 {Black's logical reaction, to clarify the situation in the center.} (8... b6 {is met with a standard positional reaction:} 9. O-O Bb7 10. cxd5 $1 {[%csl Rb7,Gd5] When the bishop is commited to b7, we can take on d5.} exd5 11. Rc1 $14 {This is typical slightly better advantage for White, that was reached in the game Sebenik-Niemann, 1-0, Bassano Mix GM 2021.}) 9. O-O (9. Rc1 $5 {This move deserves attention.} cxd4 10. cxd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd4 $14 {[%csl Gg2] +0.30, very pleasant Catalan advantage.}) 9... b5 $1 {[%csl Bb5] This is Black's hope.} (9... cxd4 {Similar to 9.Rc1.} 10. cxd5 $1 Nxd5 11. Nxd4 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gd1b3,Gf1d1,Gd7f6] The advantage is slightly bigger, cause White can first focus on fighting for the d-file.}) 10. cxd5 Nxd5 {This is the best, but still, it doesn't equalize:} (10... exd5 $6 {Positionally not great.} 11. dxc5 $1 Nxc5 12. Rc1 $14 {[%csl Rd5,Re7] Just a great IQP version for White, Black is overextended on the queenside, and the knight on e7 is not great.}) 11. Ne4 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Re4c5] This is a very good option, to force Black to do something about the c-pawn.} c4 12. b3 cxb3 13. axb3 {[%csl Ra6,Gb3,Rb5,Gd4,Gg2] White reaches a familiar Catalan structure, with a slight advantage.} Bb7 14. Nd6 $1 {Semi-concrete idea.} Bc6 15. Rc1 Nb8 $1 {Best move.} 16. Ne4 $14 {[%cal Ge4c5] The knight goes to c5.}) 6. Nbd2 Nf6 7. g3 {My recommendation, we aim for a Catalan/Bogo Indian type of position.} (7. Rc1 {[%csl Gc1][%cal Ge2e3,Rc7c5] This is also a logical plan, to continue development with e3, while the rook on c1 is useful against the c5 break.} O-O {However 4 years ago, I showed the correct way to play for Black, in the game Mendonca-Basso, Paleochora op 2021:} 8. e3 Nbd7 $1 {[%csl Od7] looks strange, since it drops the c7 pawn, but the point is:} 9. cxd5 e5 $1 {[%csl Be5] Key move.} 10. Rxc7 {The young talent took the pawn, but I had an easy time equalizing:} (10. dxe5 $5 {Engine suggests this move, but it's not enough for an advantage:} Nxe5 11. Nxe5 Qxe5 12. Nc4 Qxd5 13. Qxd5 Nxd5 14. h4 $146 {Engine shows +0.10, but objectively, I think that Black is doing absolutely fine with any move:} Rd8 $11 {I guess at maximum the endgame is playable for White.}) 10... exd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd5 12. Rc1 Nxe3 $3 {[%csl Ge3] The point of my preparation.} 13. Qe2 {White went for the endgame:} (13. fxe3 $2 {fails tactically.} Qxe3+ 14. Ne2 Ne5 $1 $15 {[%csl Re1][%cal Ge5d3] With advantage for Black.}) 13... Nd5 14. Qxe7 Nxe7 $11 {But 10 moves later, we agreed to a draw, the endgame is just equal.}) 7... b6 $1 {[%csl Bb6] The best move order, and the only critical try where Black is fighting for equality in this line. I was the first player to employ it in classical chess, in the decisive round of Paleochora Open 2021, against GM Ioannidis.} (7... O-O {Most common move.} 8. Bg2 b6 {Black's main plan, but soon we will see why this is not the correct move order.} (8... Rd8 {Common try.} 9. O-O $14 {[%csl Ra6] We have seen a similar position in the Bogo-Indian, but here Black also wasted a move on ...a6, which is for sure in White's favor.}) (8... Nbd7 9. Rc1 $1 {[%csl Rc7] Good tempo, to attack c7.} c6 10. O-O e5 $5 {[%csl Ge5] Black tried this positional plan in some games, and realistically, it's the only thing that Black can aim for.} 11. cxd5 $5 {[%csl Gd5] We can go for this simple approach.} e4 {This seems logical, and here, remember the key move:} (11... cxd5 {Not challenging.} 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. e3 $14 {[%csl Rd5] Not the only move, just a favorable IQP position.}) 12. d6 $1 {[%csl Bd6][%cal Rc6d5] Important intermezzo, to not allow Black to consolidate the structure.} Qxd6 13. Nc4 $1 {[%cal Gf3d2] Another good inclusion, the knight is going to d2.} Qe7 14. Nfd2 $14 {[%cal Gd1b3,Gb3a3,Ye7a3,Yb2a3] A typical idea in this structure is to go for the endgame with Qb3-Qa3, followed by bxa3!?, to open the b-file for the rook as well.}) (8... c5 {[%csl Rb6] This is a logical idea, but you see how the a6 move is not really helping Black at this moment.} 9. dxc5 Qxc5 10. Rc1 $1 {[%csl Rb6,Rc5][%cal Gd2c4] Black has some concrete problems.} Qe7 $1 $146 {Best move for Black.} (10... dxc4 {was played in the only game that this position was reached.} 11. Nxc4 b5 $4 12. Nd6 $1 $18 {[%csl Rc5,Rc8] Black just resigned, cause he is losing material by force.} Qb4+ 13. Qd2 Qxd2+ 14. Nxd2 $1 $18 {[%csl Ra8,Rc8] Double-attack.}) 11. cxd5 exd5 $1 {Necessary, to control the c4 square.} (11... Nxd5 12. O-O $16 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ge2e4,Gd2c4] White has a serious positional advantage.}) 12. O-O Nc6 13. Nb3 $14 {[%csl Rd5] Once again, we are ready to play against the IQP.}) 9. O-O Bb7 10. Rc1 c5 {Critical move.} (10... Rc8 {[%cal Gb8d7] Black's most common move, to prepare Nbd7, while c7 is protected.} 11. cxd5 $1 {Our standard positional reaction.} exd5 12. Re1 $14 {[%csl Rc7,Rd5] We are more than ready to play this structure.}) 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Ra6,Bb3,Rb6] Very strong move, once again 3...a6 didn't help Black at all.} Qc7 {Black must defend the pawn this way.} (12... Nbd7 $4 {Just drops material.} 13. dxc5 $1 {[%csl Rb6] The b6 pawn is lost.} Nxc5 14. Qxb6 $18) 13. dxc5 $1 {[%csl Gc5] Good moment to got for the hanging pawns structure, since with the extra tempi, White can easily attack them.} bxc5 14. Qa3 Nbd7 15. Nb3 c4 $1 {Necessary move, but it's a big positional concession.} (15... Rac8 $2 {was played in the game Antic-Budisavljevic, Belgrade 2021, but it fails tactically.} 16. Nxc5 $1 Nxc5 17. b4 $1 $18 {[%csl Gb4,Rc5,Rc7] The point.}) 16. Na5 Rac8 {We are following the game Sargsyan-Indjic, EU-ch 2022.} 17. b3 $1 $146 {[%csl Gb3,Rc4] This is my recommendation, to play for activity.} (17. Nxb7 {White went for a solid approach.} Qxb7 18. b3 cxb3 19. axb3 $14 {It's slightly more pleasant for White, but Black is also quite happy, since there are less pieces on the board.}) 17... Ba8 $1 {[%csl Ba8] Black should find this.} 18. bxc4 Qc5 $1 {[%csl Bc5] Not so difficult moves, but it requires some calculation.} 19. Qxc5 Rxc5 20. Nb3 Rxc4 21. Nfd2 {Material is balanced, but the endgame is slightly better for White, of course, thanks to the better structure.} Ra4 22. Rc2 $14 {[%csl Gc1,Gc2][%cal Gf1c1] White is in control of the position.}) (7... dxc4 {Black has tried this concrete move in some games.} 8. Nxc4 Nc6 $1 {This is the best, with a tricky nuance in mind.} (8... b5 $2 {Common mistake, used by GM Andreikin in some blitz games.} 9. Na5 $1 {[%csl Ba5] Key move, and White has a serious positional advantage.} O-O 10. Rc1 $16 {[%csl Rc7] The c7 pawn is the main target, along with all the weak squares on the c-file.}) (8... Qb4+ {doesn't achieve much.} 9. Nfd2 $1 $14 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Ga2a3,Gf1g2] The queen must go home to e7 at some point.}) 9. Nce5 $5 {I like this approach, used in the only game that reached this position: Khenkin-Fecker, 1-0, Kortschnoi Memorial 2023.} (9. Bg2 $6 {This is bad, because of:} Qb4+ $1 {[%csl Gb4] And White has concrete problems.} 10. Nfd2 Nxd4 $1 $132 {[%csl Bd4] The point.}) 9... Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Nd7 11. Bg2 Nxe5 12. dxe5 {We can check the game, because it was a high level conversion by White of his slightly better advantage:} Qc5 13. f4 Qb6 14. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Bb3] Good decision, to enter the endgame.} Qxb3 15. axb3 $14 {[%csl Rc8,Gg2][%cal Rc7c6] The endgame is very pleasant, since the bishop on g2 is a monster, while if Black wants to finish development, he needs the move c7-c6, which is a big positional concession.} Ke7 16. Kf2 Rd8 17. Rhc1 c6 {Black had no choice.} 18. Ke3 Kd7 19. b4 {[%cal Gg3g4] The next step was to take space on the kingside.} Rb8 20. g4 $1 Kc7 21. Be4 Bd7 22. h4 $1 g6 23. h5 Rg8 {White played some move, and still won the endgame, but after:} 24. Rh1 $1 $18 {[%cal Gh1h7] The rook enters on the h-file, and it's +2 evaluation.}) 8. Bg2 Bb7 9. Rc1 c5 $1 {[%csl Bc5,Ye1,Ye8] This is Black's point, they try to save on the move castle.} 10. cxd5 {White goes for the same reaction:} (10. dxc5 $5 {In my game, White took on c5, and it is a decent try.} bxc5 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nb3 $1 {[%csl Ra5,Rc5][%cal Gb3a5,Gb3c5] White went for this concrete idea.} Nbd7 13. Na5 $1 {[%csl Rb7] The bishop on b7 cannot go to a8.} Rb8 14. Nxb7 $5 {At this point, White should take the bishop.} (14. b4 $6 {Ioannidis tried this ambitious move, but it was a bit too much.} c4 $1 {And I was fine, and soon I overtook the initiative.} 15. a3 O-O 16. O-O Ba8 17. Re1 g6 18. Qd4 {This is how the game continued.} Rfe8 $36 {Improvement, and Black is doing better.}) 14... Rxb7 15. b3 O-O 16. O-O a5 17. Ne1 $132 {[%csl Gg2][%cal Ge1d3] I think that neither side should be particularly unhappy with the position they've got. White has a playable structure and a potentially strong bishop on g2, while Black has got trumps as well, more space, active rooks. It is just a playable position.}) 10... exd5 11. Qb3 Nbd7 $1 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Gd7c5] This move was just a blunder with the king on g1 and g8, but here it works!} 12. dxc5 Nxc5 13. Qa3 $1 {[%csl Ba3][%cal Rc5d3] To keep an eye on Nd3+.} (13. Qxb6 $4 {This is a blunder now!} Nd3+ $1 $19 {[%csl Rc1,Re1] And it is Black who wins material! Key difference of why Black should start with 7...b6!, not with 7...0-0 8.0-0 b6.}) 13... O-O 14. Nd4 {[%cal Ge1g1] White wants to finish development, and play a pleasant structure against the isolated pawn on d5.} Nfe4 $1 {[%csl Be4] Black must try to do something fast.} 15. Qe3 $5 $146 {[%csl Re7][%cal Ge3e7] This is a novelty, and I like it the most.} (15. N2f3 $6 {is quite slow.} a5 $1 $146 {[%cal Rb2b4] Good move to stop b4.} 16. O-O f5 $1 $132 {[%csl Gc5,Ge4][%cal Ge7f6] Black secured two very strong knights in the center of the board, and I don't see a way to pose any particular problems to Black.}) 15... Rfe8 16. O-O Qf6 {Black, very logically, unpins.} 17. Nxe4 $5 {We take on e4 now, since the queen on e3 is actually well placed against the 17...dxe4 recapture.} Nxe4 $1 {[%csl Be4] This is positionally the correct response.} (17... dxe4 $6 {Black improves the structure, but the problems don't end here.} 18. b4 $1 {[%cal Gc1c7] This is White's plan.} Ne6 19. Nxe6 Qxe6 20. Rc7 {The rook enters the game with tempo.} Bd5 21. a3 {[%csl Rb6,Re4,Gg2][%cal Gf1d1] White is slightly better, because Black has two vulnerabilities in the position: the e4 pawn (well defended now, but in an endgame it can be weak) and the queenside pawns (which thanks to the 3...a6, will remain vulnerable for the rest of the game).} Rec8 22. Rxc8+ Rxc8 23. Rd1 $14 {[%cal Gd1d4,Gh2h4,Gg1h2] Black is a bit stuck.}) 18. Rc7 $1 {White must enter the complications:} Nc5 19. Qf3 $3 {[%csl Gf3] Inviting Black to capture the d4 knight.} Qxf3 {The best.} (19... Qxd4 $4 20. b4 $3 $18 {[%csl Bb4][%cal Rd4b4,Gf3f7,Gf7g7] Key move, if Black takes on b4, it is mate after Qxf7-g7.}) 20. Bxf3 Rac8 {Black can hold it, but it will not be the most pleasant task:} 21. Rxc8 Rxc8 22. Nf5 Rc7 $1 {Strongest move.} 23. Rd1 Na4 $1 {Another precise move.} 24. Rd2 $14 {[%csl Rd5] But White is anyway slightly better, and can definitely push for a win against this isolated d5 pawn.} *

