{[%evp 0,47,30,21,29,-16,-18,-18,45,49,35,40,21,34,34,39,52,53,48,48,48,35,52,34,21,15,78,46,50,37,39,48,51,33,56,69,60,32,38,42,52,40,48,23,23,19,19,29,17,-10]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 {Welcome to the Tarrasch Unit, against it we are not going to play with g3, because it is very difficult to find something, we can go for different ideas against minor moves.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 {[%cal Gg8f6,Yb8c6] Now Black has 2 moves: Nc6 or Nf6.} Nc6 {This is the Classical Tarrasch.} (5... Nf6 6. dxc5 $6 {We don't take on c5, because it is different position and d5 is protected.} Bxc5 $11) 6. dxc5 d4 {Black's idea.} (6... Bxc5 $6 {just loses a pawn.} 7. Qxd5 {We simply have an extra pawn.} Qb6 8. e3 Nf6 9. Qb3 {The endgame is fine for White.} Qxb3 10. axb3 $16 {I don't know who will go for this position. Our structure is not the best, but a pawn is a pawn.}) (6... Nf6 {is also not great, we can support c5.} 7. Be3 {[%csl Yc5,Ge3][%cal Ge3c5] Black has no compensation.} Be7 8. g3 O-O 9. Bg2 Ng4 {Black tries to recover the pawn.} 10. Nxd5 Nxe3 11. Nxe3 $14 {Black will regain one pawn, but not enough compensation.}) 7. Na4 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Ga4c5]} Bxc5 {Regaining the pawn is of course the best.} (7... b5 $2 {It's a bad move.} 8. cxb6 axb6 9. e3 {is the correct move.} Bb4+ 10. Bd2 {Different moves have been tried, but nothing leads to something good for Black.} Bd7 {is the main move.} (10... dxe3 {The concrete try.} 11. Bxb4 Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 {Black has nothing.} Nxb4 13. Bb5+ Ke7 14. Nxb6 $18) (10... d3 11. Bxb4 Nxb4 12. Nd4 $18 {[%cal Ga4c3,Ga2a3,Gf1d3] We stop the threat, and eventually win the 2nd pawn. Black is simply lost.}) 11. Bb5 {[%csl Yd7] We close the diagonal of the bishop.} Ra5 12. Nxd4 {You need to remember a few forced moves, but position is bad for Black after} Nxd4 13. Bxb4 Nxb5 14. Bxa5 bxa5 15. O-O $18 {[%cal Ga4c5] The material advantage along with the development advantage, White has very easy play, objectively Black is simply lost.}) 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Bd2 {is my main recommendation.} (9. Qd2 $5 {This move also deserves attention.} Qxc5 {If you don't want to study anything you can just play 10.e3.} 10. a3 {is quite interesting.} (10. e3 dxe3 11. Qxe3+ Qxe3+ 12. Bxe3 {And White can play this endgame.} Nge7 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Ge3c5,Gc5f8] is mostly played to close the diagonal. Black is solid, it is not so easy win, but actually in practice, White scored 65%.} (12... Nf6 {is not so precise.} 13. Bb5 $14 {[%cal Gb5c6,Ge3c5] We can put pressure on Black's position.}) 13. Bc4 $14 {You can definetely play this risk-free position.}) 10... Nge7 {is Black's most played.} 11. b4 Qb6 12. Bb2 O-O 13. Bxd4 $5 {is more critical.} (13. Nxd4 {Black seems to equalize after} Rd8 14. e3 Nf5 $11 {Move by move play, but objectively Black achieves equality.}) 13... Nxd4 14. Qxd4 Nc6 {is Black's idea, as you see very move by move.} 15. Qb2 {Better to keep queens.} (15. Qxb6 $6 axb6 $132 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gc6b4] The pawns are weak.}) 15... a5 16. b5 a4 $1 {[%cal Gc6a5,Ga5b3] If not this move, Black is seriously worse.} 17. e3 Na5 18. Be2 Nb3 19. Rd1 Qa5+ 20. Kf1 {Of course, Black has compensation, but it is a game, for example:} Be6 21. h4 $14 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gf1g2] White needs to stabilize the king, and it is not 100% that Black will always have compensation. 9.Qd2 move is definitely playable for White.}) 9... Qxc5 10. Rc1 {I like it more.} (10. b4 $5 {also deserves attention.} Nxb4 11. Rc1 $13 {with very interesting play ahead.}) 10... Qb6 11. e3 {This is the starting position of the Classical Tarrasch. Now Black has a choice:} Nf6 {The most precise move, in my opinion.} (11... dxe3 {is quite testing.} 12. Bxe3 Qxb2 {is not so common, but at least it is concrete, and here we should remember, because it is move by move.} (12... Qb4+ {Now it is not so good.} 13. Bd2 Qe7+ 14. Be2 Nf6 15. O-O {Compared to 11...Nf6, we simply have an extra tempo, because we didn't play Bc4-Be2, but only Be2.} O-O 16. Re1 {And it is of course useful this extra tempo.} Bf5 {was played in Wojtaszek-Gajewski.} 17. Bb5 {Very good move and regrouping.} Qd8 18. Qa4 Bd7 {Now a lot of good moves, we don't need to analyze it, simply an extra tempo.} 19. Red1 $5 $14 {or 19.Qf4 also is good.} (19. Qh4 {1-0 (27) Wojtaszek,R (2694)-Gajewski,G (2596) Bydgoszcz POL 2021})) 13. Bc4 Nge7 {I think this is the best move.} (13... Qb4+ $6 {The most common move is a mistake.} 14. Nd2 Nge7 15. O-O O-O 16. Bc5 $1 {[%cal Rb4c5,Gc4f7] And it is a very dangerous position for Black.} Qb2 $1 {is the best move.} (16... Qa5 {was played in some games, but seems that White is winning after} 17. Qe2 Bf5 18. Rfe1 {Too many threats.} Rae8 (18... Rfe8 {In this case, some problems with the f7 pawn also.} 19. Ne4 Ng6 $2 20. Bxf7+ {White is winning.} Kxf7 21. Nd6+ $18) 19. Nb3 Qd8 20. Qb2 $16 {[%csl Gc4,Gc5,Re7,Re8,Rf8] White completely dominates.}) 17. Re1 Rd8 18. Rc2 {So far forced.} (18. Bxe7 Rxd2 19. Bxf7+ Kxf7 20. Qf3+ Bf5 21. Qxf5+ Kg8 22. Bg5 Rd6 23. Rcd1 $14) 18... Qf6 19. Bxe7 $146 {My novelty.} Nxe7 20. Ne4 {Nice tempo.} Qb6 21. Qh5 Qg6 22. Qh4 {And only move for Black is Kf8. Is it easy? I don't think so.} Kf8 $1 {Very strong.} (22... Nc6 {Any player would play this to defend the rook on d8, but} 23. Rc3 {[%cal Gc3g3] Rg3 next and Black is in big trouble.} Bf5 {Probably it's best already to give up the queen, but I am not sure it is a fortress after} 24. Rg3 Bxe4 25. Rxg6 Bxg6 26. Bb3 $40 {[%cal Gh4g4,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] Our pieces are very active, it looks very dangerous for Black.}) 23. Bb3 {Now another only move.} Qh6 $1 24. Qg5 {Black cannot take on g5.} Bf5 (24... Qxg5 $6 25. Nxg5 $16 {[%csl Rf7,Rh7]}) 25. Rc7 Rd7 {Okay, you can analyze forever this position, for example:} 26. Qxf5 $1 {is a strong idea.} Nxf5 27. Rxd7 Qg6 28. h3 $36 {[%cal Gg2g4] If Black plays like an engine, maybe it can hold, but not easy over the board.} h5 29. g4 hxg4 30. Rxf7+ Qxf7 31. Bxf7 Kxf7 32. hxg4 {And now we have this interesting endgame.} Nd4 33. Nd6+ Kf6 34. Kg2 {[%csl Rf6][%cal Gf2f4]} b6 35. f4 $36 {It's still a game.}) 14. Ng5 {Now we play concrete.} O-O (14... Ne5 {is logical, but bad.} 15. O-O Nxc4 16. Rxc4 O-O 17. Bc5 $1 {We are in time to creat problems.} Qf6 18. Re1 Be6 19. Nxe6 fxe6 20. Rce4 $16 {We have better organized pieces.}) 15. Qh5 {Comparing to other lines, Black is not defending an unpleasant endgame. Here it is very concrete and we need to know what to do.} Bf5 16. Bxf7+ Kh8 17. O-O h6 {has to be played.} (17... Qf6 {is not so great.} 18. f4 h6 19. g4 $36 {This seems very interesting.}) 18. Bb3 $5 {is interesting, there was only one game.} (18. Ne6 {was played in practice, but after} Bg4 $1 {Strong move.} 19. Qxg4 Rxf7 {I don't think we have much in this position.} 20. Rb1 Qxa2 21. Rxb7 Nd8 $1 {Trades the important knight.} 22. Nxd8 Rxd8 23. Rxa7 Qd5 $11 {3 vs 2, but Black has a knight and in defence on one flank it is convenient for the defending side, most likely it should end in a draw.}) 18... Bg6 $1 {is a strong novelty for Black.} (18... Qf6 {was not the most precise, but it was not easy for White to understand that after the long line:} 19. Nf7+ Kh7 20. Bg5 Qg6 21. Qxg6+ Nxg6 22. Be3 Na5 {½-½ Elsness,F (2465)-Fossum,O (2302) Fagernes op 2021 (4)} 23. Rc5 $1 {is strong, with the idea that after} Nxb3 24. Rxf5 Ne7 25. Ng5+ hxg5 26. Rxg5 {[%csl Rb3] The knight is trapped on b3.} Nf5 27. axb3 Nxe3 28. fxe3 $14 {Black can force this endgame, which maybe is holdable, but not a guaranteed draw for sure. Over the board, it should be around 40% win 60% draw.}) 19. Qh3 Qf6 20. Nf3 Be4 21. Rfd1 {This was my idea, because if Black simplifies, White has the initiative.} Rad8 {Normal try.} (21... Bxf3 22. Qxf3 Qxf3 23. gxf3 Rxf3 24. Rd7 $36 {Strong bishops and a strong rook on the 7th.}) 22. Bc5 Rfe8 23. Qh4 Qg6 {Already Black needs to calculate deep.} (23... Qxh4 24. Nxh4 $14 {The endgame is of course interesting.}) 24. Rxd8 Rxd8 25. Bxe7 Bxf3 26. Qg3 Qxg3 27. fxg3 Nxe7 28. gxf3 {[%cal Gc1c7] Rc7 is a threat.} Nc6 29. Kf2 $14 {[%cal Gc1d1] In practice, White can try to push for a win.}) 12. Bc4 (12. Qa4 {has been tried in some games, but I don't believe in this move.} O-O 13. Nxd4 Qxb2 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Qc2 {Maybe after 15...Qxc2 it is a playable for White, but} Rb8 $1 {is very precise.} 16. Bc4 Qxc2 {Now Black takes.} 17. Rxc2 Bf5 18. Rc1 Ne4 {And Black is in time to get some counterplay.} 19. Ba5 Rb2 20. O-O Nd2 21. Bxd2 Rxd2 {This endgame is difficult to win, but of course it's playable. For example:} 22. Bb3 Rc8 23. Rc5 $36 {You can put pressure risk free and play on, but of course it is quite drawish.}) 12... dxe3 (12... O-O {It is not refuted, but very very sad for Black.} 13. O-O Bg4 14. exd4 Nxd4 {The best, in my opinion.} (14... Rad8 {is the most common move, but here} 15. Bc3 Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Nxd4 17. Qf4 $14 {With 2 bishops, White can play a long game for sure.}) 15. Be3 Bxf3 16. Qxd4 {This is the point.} Qxd4 17. Bxd4 Bd5 {And now we can transform the position to a rook endgame.} 18. Bxf6 Bxc4 19. Rxc4 gxf6 {The engine will hold it, but over the board, only one game and White won.} 20. g3 $5 {is maybe also interesting. Because after the most logical continuation:} (20. Rc7 $14 {1-0 (28) Kashlinskaya,A (2481)-Wu,L (2332) FIDE Chess.com Grand Swiss Douglas 2019 (3)}) 20... Rfc8 {To exchange one rook is natural, but a bad idea actually.} 21. Rfc1 Rxc4 22. Rxc4 $14 {It is tougher to defend, so g3 is a tricky idea, to provoke Rfc8.}) 13. Bxe3 Qb4+ 14. Bd2 {We can keep more pieces on the board for now.} (14. Qd2 {You can also go for the endgame, I tried it myself, and won some games.} Qxd2+ 15. Kxd2 O-O 16. Rhd1 {It's a playable, of course engine will hold, it really depends on how much you like to play endgames in general.} Ng4 17. Ke2 $5 {Engine says that this move is stronger.} (17. h3 {I played this move, but it is not the best for some reason.}) 17... Nxe3 18. fxe3 {This is the idea, to transform the structure, and we have very active pieces.} Be6 {In case of Be6, we can already capture the d-file after} 19. Bxe6 fxe6 20. Rd7 Rf7 21. Rcd1 $14 {And this endgame can be very unpleasant.}) 14... Qe7+ 15. Be2 (15. Qe2 {is also possible.}) 15... O-O 16. O-O {We can play these positions, we have the pair of bishops after all.} Be6 {The most logical.} 17. Re1 Rfe8 18. Ng5 $5 {can be more interesting.} (18. Qa4 {was played in the high-level game, but I dont like it so much.} Bd5 19. a3 Qd7 20. Bg5 Re4 $132 {½-½ (74) Wojtaszek,R (2737)-Nisipeanu,L (2672) Dortmund GER 2019}) 18... Bd5 {Normal move.} 19. Bc3 Qd7 20. Qc2 Ne5 21. Bf1 {We hide the bishops.} Rac8 22. Qb1 $14 {Black only plays for draw without any guarantee of making it, but it is unpleasant.} Ng6 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. Rd1 $14 {We can put pressure in this middlegame.} *

