{[%evp 0,37,36,13,20,-3,-3,4,42,43,27,43,10,33,43,40,40,40,-3,41,41,32,32,49,49,-17,0,0,7,0,0,82,101,95,113,107,85,76,95,46]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nc3 Nf6 {In the past, it was considered a bit dubious, but thanks to the help of modern engines it became a very sound line, you cannot refute it, but White has interesting tries.} 6. Bg5 Be6 $1 {[%csl Ge6] The correct way to play this variation. You will face this move 99% of the time. The idea is to overprotect d5, so the queen on d8 can recapture on f6.} (6... Nc6 $2 {is also bad.} 7. Bxf6 $1 {Black has to choose between sad moves.} gxf6 (7... Qxf6 {loses a pawn for no compensation.} 8. Nxd5 Qd8 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Rc1 $16 {[%cal Ge2e3,Yf1e2,Yf1b5] Good intermezzo.}) 8. e3 $16 {[%csl Rf6,Rf7,Rh7] The structure is terrible for Black.}) (6... c4 $2 {is very bad because of} 7. e4 $1 $16 {Black's center is collapsing.} dxe4 8. Ne5 {Now everything develops with tempo.} Be7 9. Bxc4 O-O 10. Qb3 $18 {Black can resign.}) (6... cxd4 {is not great to release the tension.} 7. Nxd4 Be7 8. e3 O-O {White is better with many moves.} 9. Bb5 {[%cal Rb8c6] More creative approach to prevent Nc6.} (9. Be2 {Classical approach.} Nc6 10. O-O {White has a typical slightly better position.} Be6 11. Rc1 Rc8 12. Bf4 $5 $146 {Black's position is unpleasant. For example:} Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Bc5 14. Qd3 a6 {Black should start with a6 first, but now he is not in time.} (14... d4 {The concrete plan doesn't work.} 15. Na4 $1 $16) 15. Bf3 $14 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gf3b7,Gc3e2,Ge2d4] Black cannot push d4 because problems with b7 pawn, and otherwise we maneuver Ne2-d4, with a long game ahead.}) 9... a6 10. Ba4 $14 {We keep control of the c6 square and it is unpleasant to play.} b5 (10... Bg4 {followed by Nbd7 should be considered, but White is better after many moves.}) 11. Bb3 $14 {Still no Nc6.}) (6... Be7 7. dxc5 O-O 8. e3 Be6 {White has a choice:} 9. Be2 {Classical way is good, as usual.} (9. Bb5 {also possible.} Bxc5 10. O-O {We again threaten Bxf6.} Be7 (10... Nc6 11. Bxf6 $16) 11. Nd4 {[%cal Rb8c6] No Nc6.} a6 12. Ba4 $14) 9... Bxc5 10. O-O Nc6 11. Rc1 {Typical game.} Be7 {is necessary.} (11... a6 $2 12. Bxf6 {We win a pawn.} Qxf6 13. Nxd5 $16) 12. a3 $14 {2 results game ahead.}) 7. Bxf6 {is my recommendation, we play very concrete.} (7. e3 {I don't like e3, Black can play} c4 {[%csl Ge3,Ge6] And it is not the same as 6...c4.} 8. Be2 (8. e4 Bb4 $132 {Black is absolutely fine.}) 8... Bb4 {Black's position is absolutely playable.} 9. O-O O-O 10. Ne5 Nbd7 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. Bxf6 gxf6 {Black has a bad structure, but pretty solid.} 13. Bf3 Kg7 14. e4 {Sooner or later, White plays this move.} dxe4 15. Bxe4 Rfe8 16. a3 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Bf5 $11) 7... Qxf6 {The idea behind 6...Be6.} (7... gxf6 $2 8. e3 c4 {[%cal Gf1e2] The difference between this line and 7.e3 is that our bishop was on e2.} 9. g3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gf1g2] The bishop is much stronger on g2.} Nc6 10. Bg2 Bb4 11. O-O O-O 12. Nh4 $16 {[%cal Gd1h5] Black is in deep trouble.}) 8. e4 dxe4 {is the main move.} (8... cxd4 $2 {is a mistake because of} 9. Bb5+ $1 {And White has an almost winning advantage.} Nd7 (9... Nc6 10. Nxd5 $18) 10. Bxd7+ Kxd7 (10... Bxd7 11. Nxd5 $18) 11. Qb3 $18 {The king is in the center.}) (8... Nd7 {When I first analyzed this position in 2019, this move didn't exist, but now engines show that it is playable.} 9. Bb5 {is my recommendation.} (9. exd5 Bg4 {is Black's idea.}) 9... O-O-O {That's why Black first castles.} (9... cxd4 $2 10. Bxd7+ $18 {was seen under 8...cxd4.}) 10. O-O cxd4 {is the best move for Black, played in Kjartansson-Kasimdzhanov, Bundesliga 2024.} (10... Nb6 $2 {was played in the game Aditya-Abdusattorov, but it is a serious mistake.} 11. e5 $146 Qg6 12. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5]} a5 {[%csl Rc8] Long castle mixed with a5 is of course not a great idea for Black.} 13. Qd2 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Gd2a5] The pawn is very weak.} c4 14. Na2 {No Bb4.} Bh3 15. Ne1 $16 {We defend everything and can win a pawn next.}) 11. Bxd7+ Rxd7 12. e5 {It's a fresh position, because only one game.} Qd8 $1 {Kasimdzhanov played the best move.} (12... Qg6 {would be a normal move, but White is slightly better.} 13. Qxd4 (13. Nb5 {leads to the same.} Kb8 14. Qxd4 $14) 13... Kb8 14. Nb5 b6 15. Qc3 {looks very interesting.} d4 $1 {Only move.} 16. Nfxd4 Bd5 17. g3 {Probably some compensation for Black, but not enough.} Bc5 18. b4 Bxd4 19. Qxd4 $14 {[%cal Gb5d6,Gf2f4]}) 13. Nxd4 {The best move in my opinion, also played in the game.} (13. Nb5 Qb6 $11 {[%csl Gb6] The queen is well placed.}) (13. Qxd4 {is an interesting try.} Qa5 14. a3 Kb8 $1 {The best for the engine.} (14... Bc5 15. Qf4 $14 {[%cal Gb2b4]}) 15. b4 Qa6 16. Qe3 $14 {[%cal Gf3d4,Gc3e2,Ge2f4,Ye2d4,Yd4e6] I am not sure that Black equalizes here 100%.}) 13... Kb8 $1 {Important prophylactic and only move.} (13... Be7 {Black has very serious problems after} 14. Ncb5 Kb8 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Nd4 Qb6 17. Qg4 $16 {[%csl Re6] Not clear how to defend e6.}) 14. a3 $5 {is an useful move.} (14. f4 {was played in the game, but I don't like this idea.} g6 15. Rf2 Bc5 16. Na4 Bxd4 17. Qxd4 Rc7 $11 {[%cal Gd8d7,Gh8c8] Black's position is absolutely fine. ½- (48) ½ Kjartansson,G (2453)-Kasimdzhanov,R (2673) Bundesliga 2324 Germany 2023 (5.5)}) (14. Qd2 $5 {could be another try, to save a tempo on a3.} Bc5 15. Rfc1 Bb6 (15... a6 {is not great anymore.} 16. Na4 Ba7 17. Nc5 {Completely another version.} Rc7 18. Ndxe6 fxe6 19. Nxe6 Rxc1+ 20. Rxc1 Qd7 21. Nc5 $14 {We take with the rook compared to the 14.a3 line.}) 16. Na4 Bxd4 17. Qxd4 Rc7 18. Nc5 $14 {[%cal Gc1c3,Ga1c1] Slightly better for White, but not refuted.}) 14... Bc5 15. Rc1 a6 {[%cal Gc5a7] With the idea to keep the bishop on a7 is the best.} (15... Bxd4 {Taking on d4 is not the same now.} 16. Qxd4 Qa5 17. Ne2 $14 {[%cal Ge2d4] White obviously has an edge and you can play slowly.}) 16. Na4 Ba7 17. Nc5 {We can play this way, now Black needs to find} Rc7 $1 {Maybe not an easy move.} 18. Ndxe6 fxe6 19. Nxe6 Rxc1 20. Qxc1 Qd7 21. Nc5 {We have an extra pawn, but Black can regain it after} Qf5 $1 22. b4 Bxc5 23. Qxc5 Qxe5 24. Rc1 Rd8 $11 {Black equalizes, but we are very far. As I told you, you cannot refute this move.}) 9. Nxe4 Qf4 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Rf4][%cal Gf4e4] Black's only idea. The queen is safe on f4, and I want to show you two directions: one classical and a new one that I discovered in 2019.} (9... Qd8 $2 {is a mistake after} 10. Qa4+ $16 Bd7 11. Bb5 {White has a very serious advantage, for example:} cxd4 12. Nxd4 Be7 13. Nf5 O-O $4 {loses material.} 14. Bxd7 Nxd7 15. Rd1 $18 {[%csl Rd7]}) 10. Nfg5 $5 {A very funny and fresh idea.} (10. Bb5+ {The classical direction.} Nc6 {has to be played.} 11. Qe2 Be7 {is a very serious move.} (11... O-O-O $6 {is a bit dubious, in my opinion.} 12. Bxc6 bxc6 13. O-O Bd5 {is the idea, concrete move.} (13... cxd4 {looks logical, but} 14. Rad1 {[%cal Rc6c5,Ge2a6] Not so easy to play this position for Black.} d3 $1 {Best move.} 15. Rxd3 Rxd3 16. Qxd3 {Black has two bishops, but look at the structure and the king on c8.} Bd5 $1 17. Re1 Bb4 18. g3 {The only thing we need to find, where in return Black needs to play} Qc7 $1 {Only move.} 19. Nc3 $14 {+0.50, I guess it is not the way Black wants to play.}) 14. Rfe1 {Some games have been played.} Kb8 $1 {The best move.} (14... Kb7 {Natural move, but not the best.} 15. Qc2 cxd4 16. Rad1 $1 $40 {It looks very dangerous for Black.} Bb4 $4 17. Rxd4 $1 $18 {[%csl Rb7,Rf4][%cal Rb4e1,Ge4c5]}) (14... Bxe4 {possible, but very passive.} 15. Qxe4 Qxe4 16. Rxe4 {Black doesn't even have the bishop's pair anymore.} cxd4 17. Nxd4 $14 {[%csl Ra7,Rc6,Gd4] Better endgame, +0.50, a dream for everyone.}) (14... cxd4 $6 {was played by strong players like Nihal and Gukesh.} 15. g3 {[%csl Rf4] is strong though.} Qc7 16. Nxd4 $14 {[%csl Rc8,Gd4,Ge4] It is not very big advantage, but unpleasant one.}) 15. Nxc5 {We can take here simply.} (15. Qc2 cxd4 16. Nxd4 $5 {is another interesting idea.} (16. Rad1 {is not the same as in the Kb7 line.} Bb4 $1 17. Rxd4 $2 Bxe1 $19 {[%csl Gb8,Rf4][%cal Ge4c5] And no check on c5.}) 16... Bb4 17. Re3 c5 18. g3 Qc7 19. Nb5 Qc6 20. Nbc3 $14 {Playable for White.}) 15... Bxc5 16. dxc5 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Qxf3 18. gxf3 $14 {Maybe it will not be easy to convert the advantage, but the draw is not guaranteed for Black.}) 12. O-O O-O {The start of a concrete line.} 13. Nxc5 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxc5 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. Rac1 {We can play solid for now.} (16. Qxe6+ {If we take on e6 early,} Kh8 $44 {[%csl Re6,Gf2][%cal Gc5f2,Ra8d8,Rd8d2] and Black's counterplay is quite fast.}) 16... b6 17. Rc4 Qg5 {is probably the best move, but difficult to understand for a player.} (17... Qf6 18. Re4 $14 {Look at the position, not a funny one to play from the Black side, but objectively Black can hold.}) 18. Rg4 Qe7 19. g3 $14 {[%csl Re6] White can play a long game, I would be happy to have it over the board, but if you feel that it is too little, I offer you the 10.Nfg5 idea also.}) 10... c4 $1 {[%cal Gf8b4] The best move for Black, the idea is Bb4+.} (10... cxd4 $2 {is not good.} 11. Qxd4 {This was the game Ponkratov-Bejtovic.} Nc6 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Bb5 Bc5 {was played in the game, where Ponkratov responded with 14.Qc4 and eventually won, but} 14. Nf6+ {was even stronger.} Qxf6 15. Qxc5 Kf7 16. Bxc6 bxc6 17. O-O $16 {Black is at least worst.} Qxb2 $2 18. Rab1 $18 {[%cal Gb1b7,Gb1b3,Gb3f3]}) (10... Nc6 {was tried in the game Poltorak-Frank.} 11. g3 Qf5 {was the best, but already Black needs to look out for some complicated things:} (11... Qc7 {was played in the game, but after} 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. dxc5 $16 {White is just better and later won a nice game.}) 12. Bh3 Qg6 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. dxc5 {It is not so comfortable to play for Black.} h6 {is a nice trick.} 15. Qd3 $1 Qf5 (15... hxg5 $2 16. Nd6+ $18 {[%csl Rg6]}) 16. Nf3 {[%csl Ge4] The knight is now defended.} Rd8 17. Qe3 $14 {[%csl Rc5,Re6] Engine can hold even this, shows +0.20 only, but even if Black plays all the best moves and regains c5 we can play a long game against the e6 pawn.}) 11. Qd2 {We go for the endgame.} Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 {is my offer and was played only in one game (Nagly-Terkiewicz, Wroclaw Open 2024). But I analyzed this position many years ago, so it is a surprise for me that only 1 game was played so far.} (12. Nxd2 {I don't like Nxd2, Black is pretty fine here.} Nc6 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Bxc4 Nxd4 $11 {This was the game Tan-Harika, Woman Grand Prix 2023. Black has no problems in the endgame, compared to what we have seen in the 10.Bb5+ line, here it is a dream position for Black.}) 12... Nc6 $146 {is the best. Taking on e6 is needed now.} (12... Bb4+ {was played in the game.} 13. Ke3 Bd5 14. Rc1 b5 15. b3 {So far normal moves.} Nd7 {The best move.} (15... Ba3 $2 {was a mistake played in the game, because of} 16. Rc3 $1 b4 17. Rxc4 {We sac the exchange, but position is just winning.} Bxc4 18. Bxc4 $18 {[%csl Ra3,Ra8,Rf7][%cal Gc4d5] Look at that bishop on a3.}) 16. bxc4 bxc4 17. Bxc4 Bxc4 18. Rxc4 Nb6 19. Rc6 $14 {Engine may hold, it's +0.30, who will like to play this with Black? I think it is easier to win this with White than to make a draw with Black.}) 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Bxc4 Nxd4 {It is the same as the Tan-Harika endgame, but here our king is closer to the center.} 15. Kc3 e5 $1 {Best try.} (15... O-O-O 16. Rad1 g6 $1 {Only move actually, with the point that Black's knight is defended.} 17. Ng5 (17. Rxd4 $2 {is impossible.} Bg7 $17 {White loses material.}) 17... Bg7 18. Nf7 $1 {Very precise move.} Nc6+ $1 {Only move.} 19. Kc2 Rxd1 20. Rxd1 Rf8 21. Bxe6+ $14 {Maybe Black will make a draw, but pawn down, we can play this endgame forever.}) 16. f4 Nc6 {is logical to protect e5.} (16... O-O-O $6 {is dubious because of} 17. Ng5 $16 {Nf7 is coming and it is difficult to protect against it.}) 17. fxe5 Nxe5 18. Bb5+ Ke7 (18... Kf7 {maybe not precise.} 19. Rhf1+ Kg6 20. Rad1 $36 {Some initiative.}) 19. Rhe1 $36 {The position is fresh, Black had to find a lot of moves to reach this position, even here White has the initiative, because of the king on e7. Against the engine, it is a draw of course, but over the board, I guarantee you that White can definitely win positions like this.} *

