{[%evp 0,51,18,-15,6,-5,-7,-8,-7,-7,17,18,18,10,18,23,38,25,25,28,20,21,18,15,19,-28,0,24,43,13,0,10,46,43,40,41,80,19,46,60,60,63,87,56,60,53,66,81,64,59,41,59,52,27] I’m now including a chapter from “1.c4 e6 for White according to Jobava,” to offer you an additional option against the Tarrasch.} 1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg2 c5 5. cxd5 exd5 6. d4 Nc6 (6... Be7 {doesn't have independent value.} 7. O-O O-O 8. Nc3 {Black usually plays Nc6 anyways, transposing to the main line.}) (6... cxd4 7. Nxd4 Bc5 8. O-O {With the knight on b8, this is not too dangerous.} O-O 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Nb3 Bb6 11. Bg5 Be6 {Logical.} (11... d4 12. Nd5 $14) 12. a4 $1 {Good inclusion.} a6 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. Qxd5 Qxb2 16. Rab1 $14 {Problems with the b6 bishop.}) 7. O-O (7. Nc3 {Don't start with this, since it allows Black an extra line:} cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bc5 $11 {The so called Dubov Tarrasch, and it is equal everywhere.}) 7... Be7 {The main line.} (7... c4 {A bit premature, in my opinion, but it's played from time to time.} 8. b3 $1 {Good timing.} cxb3 {Necessary move.} (8... b5 $2 {Black is lost, too ambitious to play like this.} 9. Bg5 {is a simple way.} (9. Nc3 b4 10. e4 $3 {is one concrete way.} bxc3 11. exd5 $18 {[%csl Rc6,Re8] The threats are too big, +3 position.}) 9... Be6 10. Ne5 Rc8 11. a4 a6 {Black loses by force after} 12. axb5 axb5 13. bxc4 bxc4 14. Qa4 Bd7 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Bxf6 gxf6 17. Nc3 Nxd4 18. Qxd7+ Kxd7 19. Rfd1 $18 {+5 advantage.}) 9. Qxb3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Gb1c3,Gc1g5,Gf3e5] If Black plays normal moves, White's advantage is simple, just play against the d5 isolated pawn.} Be7 10. Bg5 $1 {Better way to develop.} (10. Nc3 {is not so precise.} O-O 11. Bg5 Na5 $1 {[%csl Rb3] The queen comes under some tempi.} 12. Qc2 Be6 $132 {[%csl Rc2] Black is doing fine here.}) 10... Na5 {The most principled.} (10... O-O {less dangerous.} 11. Rc1 Na5 12. Qd1 {[%csl Gc1,Bd1] We are in time to place the queen on a great square.} Ne4 (12... Be6 13. Nc3 Rc8 14. Ne1 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ge1d3,Gd3f4,Ge2e3] White is slightly better.}) 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. Nc3 Nxc3 15. Rxc3 Nc4 16. Ne1 $14 {[%cal Ge1d3,Ge2e3,Ga2a4] This is exactly what White is aiming for, long term slightly better advantage.}) 11. Qb5+ $1 $146 {Good interemezzo.} Bd7 12. Qd3 O-O 13. Nc3 {[%csl Gd3,Rd7] Black will anyway need to move the bishop, but our queen is much better placed.} Be6 14. Ne5 Rc8 15. Rab1 $5 {[%csl Rb7] Good move against Nc4, since b7 is hanging.} (15. f4 {is a bit early now.} Nc6 $1 {Strong move.} 16. f5 Nxd4 $3 {The tactics begin.} 17. fxe6 Rxc3 $1 18. Qd2 Rc2 $11 {New interesting position, but I think Black is fine objectively.}) 15... h6 (15... b6 16. f4 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Ra5c6,Ge5c6] Good moment now, since Nc6 is met with Nxc6 and no bxc6.} g6 (16... Nc6 $2 {Just loses material.} 17. Nxc6 $1 Rxc6 18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. f5 $18 {[%csl Rd5] d5 drops.}) 17. Rbc1 {The rook did it's job provoking b6, now it belongs on the c-file.} Nc4 18. Nxc4 dxc4 (18... Rxc4 $2 {allows} 19. Nxd5 $1 $18 {Winning material.}) 19. Qd2 {[%cal Ge2e4] If White gets e4 in Black is just lost, that's why Black's only chance is} b5 $3 {But difficult to believe that somebody will play like this.} 20. Nxb5 Bd5 $1 21. Nc3 {Also here, White is slightly better.} Bxg2 22. Kxg2 Nd5 23. e4 Nxc3 24. Rxc3 $14 {Pawn up, Black doesn't have enough compensation.}) 16. Bd2 $5 {This is my recommendation.} (16. Bxf6 {can be considered, but Black can organize counterplay after} Bxf6 17. f4 Bxe5 $1 {Strong move.} 18. dxe5 (18. fxe5 Qd7 $132 {[%cal Gc8c4,Gf8c8,Gb7b6] Counterplay on the c-file, Black is doing fine.}) 18... d4 $1 {[%csl Ra2] a2 pawn is hanging.} 19. Nb5 Bxa2 20. Rb2 Bd5 21. Bh3 Rc5 22. Qxd4 b6 23. Rd1 $132 {Close to equal position for Black, but quite interesting.}) 16... b6 17. f4 {[%cal Gf4f5] Typical idea, f5 is our threat.} Nc6 {Safer.} (17... Nc4 {The most logical, and Black has to find a fantastic resource after:} 18. f5 Bd7 19. Nxd5 Nxe5 20. dxe5 Bc5+ 21. Kh1 Nxd5 22. Bxd5 Bc6 23. e4 {looks hopeless for Black, but ...} Qxd5 $3 {Brilliant queen sacrifice.} 24. exd5 Rfd8 $1 {[%cal Gd8d5] The point.} 25. h4 Rxd5 26. Qxd5 Bxd5+ 27. Kh2 Bxa2 $44 {[%csl Gc5,Gd2][%cal Gb1a1,Gb1c1] Black has close to full compensation for the exchange, although if White manages to trade one pair of bishops, it can be immediately lost.}) 18. f5 {Direct approach.} (18. e3 {Positional approach.} Re8 19. Rf2 Bf8 20. h3 $14 {[%cal Gg3g4] Slowly improve the position.}) 18... Bd7 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 20. Bxd5 Bxf5 $1 {The point, but the forced line only starts:} 21. Bxf7+ {Intermezzo.} Rxf7 22. Rxf5 Nxe5 23. Rxe5 Bf6 24. Re4 Qd5 25. a3 $14 {Black has almost full compensation, but White keeps the extra pawn and the chances for an advantage.}) (7... cxd4 $6 {This is senseless now.} 8. Nxd4 Bc5 {[%csl Rc5,Gg1] White played castle instead of Nc3, that's why this is worse.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Qc2 {[%csl Rc6] Problems with the c6 pawn.} Qb6 11. Nc3 Be7 12. e4 $16 {White is better.}) (7... h6 {Black stops Bg5, but it's a slow move.} 8. Nc3 c4 {makes sense, since there is no Bg5, but White can use another idea:} (8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Bc5 {The Dubov Tarrasch tempo down is not interesting:} 10. Nb3 Bb6 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Qxd5 Qxd5 13. Bxd5 O-O {This endgame is fine with the king on e1, but here many moves are interesting, for example:} 14. Be3 $5 Bxe3 15. fxe3 {[%csl Rf7] Pressure on f7.} Nb4 $1 16. Bc4 Bh3 17. Rfc1 $14 {White has a real advantage here.}) 9. Ne5 $1 {Especially good against slow setups.} Bb4 10. e4 $1 {The critical move, to fight for an advantage.} Bxc3 {Black must go for the complications, where at maximum they can survive:} 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. bxc3 Nxe4 13. Ba3 {To stop castle.} (13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Ba3 {is the same.}) 13... Be6 14. Bxe4 dxe4 15. Re1 {is a concrete try.} (15. Rb1 $5 {Positional play is also fine.} Qd7 16. Rb2 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gd1b1,Gb2b7,Gb1e4] White prepares Qb1.} f5 17. Qb1 Rc8 18. f3 exf3 19. g4 $1 {[%csl Gg6] To fight for the g6 square.} g6 (19... fxg4 {Too dangerous.} 20. Re1 $40 {[%csl Re8] Big attack.}) 20. Rb7 Rc7 21. Rb8+ Rc8 22. Qb7 {White has a lot of pressure even in the endgame.} Kf7 23. gxf5 gxf5 24. Qxd7+ Bxd7 25. Rb7 $36 {[%csl Rd7,Rf7] No coordination from Black.}) 15... f5 16. f3 Kf7 17. fxe4 fxe4 18. Rxe4 {White wins material back, and it's all about if Black can consolidate:} Re8 19. Qe2 Bd5 {Yes, but at what cost?} 20. Rxe8 Qxe8 21. Rf1+ Kg8 22. Rf8+ Qxf8 23. Bxf8 Rxf8 24. h4 $16 {Black should understand if it is a fortress or not, difficult to say.}) 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bf4 $5 {This is my recommendation, it is very rare compared to the main line (800 games and not 10K games in 9.Bg5), it is a good move, just to have a game of chess.} c4 {The most critical move.} (9... Bg4 {Common move, but doesn't pose concrete problems.} 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Qb3 $14 {Typical IQP structure, Black didn't equalize.}) (9... Bf5 {Same spirit.} 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Qb3 $14 {White has a pleasant position.}) (9... a6 {Waiting move.} 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Rc1 {The bishop is vulnerable on c5.} Ba7 {Human move.} (11... d4 12. Na4 Ba7 13. Ne5 $14) 12. Bg5 {[%csl Ra7,Ge7] Since the bishop is on a7, not on e7, we can use the pin.} Be6 13. b3 $5 $14 {[%csl Rb2,Rd5][%cal Gg5f6,Gc3d5] Tricky move, so the pawn doesn't hang on b2.}) (9... Be6 {The most common move.} 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Ng5 $1 {Good move, played in Gelfand-Mamedov, 2023.} (11. Rc1 {The main move, but quite slow.} h6 $1 $11 {stopping Ng5, Black has a more or less compact setup.}) 11... Re8 {was how the game continued, but after} (11... Qd7 {Quite empty move, the queen might also be in danger after} 12. Rc1 Be7 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. e4 $1 {Strong move.} d4 15. Bh3 $1 $36 {[%csl Rd7,Re6][%cal Gc3e2,Ge4e5] Another tactical trick, White has the initiative.}) 12. Rc1 Bf8 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Qb3 $5 $146 {Nice improvement.} Qb6 15. Qxb6 axb6 16. a3 $14 {White has a slightly better endgame, thanks to the better structure.}) (9... h6 {Useful move.} 10. Rc1 {Good way, to put pressure on the c-file.} (10. dxc5 {White can play in the typical spirit.} Bxc5 11. Rc1 Re8 12. Nb5 $5 $146 {Already new position.} Bb6 13. Nd6 Re7 (13... Re6 $2 {Not possible, because of the tactical trick:} 14. Nxc8 Rxc8 15. Bh3 $16 {[%csl Rc8,Re6] Winning material.}) 14. b4 $36 {Interesting position.}) 10... c4 {Most logical.} (10... Re8 $6 {is met with} 11. Nb5 $36 {[%csl Rc7] issues on the c7 square.}) (10... a6 {Stops Nb5, but Black played 2 pawn moves while White-two developing ones:} 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Ne5 {White has good chances after} Bd6 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. Re1 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Rd5][%cal Ge2e4] The weak structure is a long term target.}) 11. Ne5 $1 {Typical idea we have seen already.} Bf5 12. g4 $1 {Nice tempo, since the pawn is immune.} Bh7 (12... Be6 13. h3 Bb4 14. Bh2 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4] Easy play next.}) (12... Nxg4 $2 13. Nxg4 Bxg4 14. Nxd5 $16 {The central pawn is more important, of course.}) 13. a3 {against Bb4.} Na5 {Black goes for the b3 square, but it highlights a nice idea:} 14. e3 Nb3 15. Rc2 $1 {The rook is actually immune from capture.} Bd6 $1 {The only move.} (15... Bxc2 $2 16. Qxc2 $18 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gg4g5] White has probably a winning attack on the kingside.}) 16. Re2 $36 {White can continue to put pressure.}) (9... cxd4 $6 {against 9.Bg5 makes sense, but here it is dubious:} 10. Nxd4 $14 {[%csl Gh6,Rh7] White is just slightly better, the tempo h6 is very useful for Black.}) 10. Ne5 h6 {Useful move.} (10... Be6 $2 {Black's main response against 9.Bg5 line, but here it is a huge difference:} 11. Nxc4 $1 {[%csl Gf4] This tactical trick is possible.} dxc4 12. d5 $1 {[%csl Bd5,Gf4,Rg5][%cal Rf6d5] The point is that Nxd5 doesn't attack the bishop on g5.} Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Bf6 14. Bc7 $1 $18 {Black is lost due to the poor pawn structure.}) (10... Bf5 {doens't have independent value.} 11. a3 h6 12. Qd2 {transposes to the main line.}) 11. a3 $5 {[%cal Re7b4] We can stop Bb4.} Bf5 $1 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gf5b1,Re2e4] The best move, to control the diagonal and the e4 break.} (11... Be6 $2 {is again bad, because of:} 12. Nxc4 $1 {Trick.} dxc4 13. d5 $16) (11... Na5 $6 12. Qc2 {[%cal Ga1d1,Ge2e4] White has a crushing initiative in the center.} Nb3 13. Rad1 $16 {Close to winning position.}) 12. Qd2 $146 {The position is new, the game can continue with:} Re8 (12... Rc8 13. Rad1 Re8 {To put pressure on the e-file.} (13... a6 14. g4 $1 {[%cal Rf6g4,Gc3d5] Here we can push g4 immediately.} Bh7 15. Qe3 $40 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gg4g5] Big attack.}) 14. h3 $5 $36 {[%cal Gg3g4] g4 next, initiative for White.}) 13. Rad1 Bf8 14. Kh1 $5 {[%cal Gf2f3,Ge2e4,Yg3g4] Useful move, to get the king to safety, f3 comes next with both g4 or e4 in mind.} Rc8 15. f3 Bh7 {Human move, but White has an extra interesting possibility:} (15... Be6 {Prophylaxis against e4.} 16. g4 {We can get some space.} Nd7 17. Nxd7 Qxd7 18. e4 Ne7 19. h3 $14 {[%cal Gf4g3,Gf3f4] Slowly Bg3-f4, slightly better for White.}) 16. Ng4 $5 {[%csl Rd5] To put pressure against the d5 pawn.} Nxg4 17. fxg4 g5 $1 {The best, and Black can try to hold on with} 18. Be3 Na5 $1 19. Bg1 Nb3 $1 20. Qe1 {d5 is hanging, but Black doesn't care:} Rc6 $1 {Cold shower.} 21. Qf2 Qd7 22. Bxd5 Qxd5+ $3 {This is the point.} 23. Nxd5 Be4+ 24. Qf3 Bxf3+ 25. exf3 Bg7 26. f4 $14 {Black has almost full compensation, but it's still playable endgame.} *

