{[%evp 0,52,36,36,57,57,60,55,55,51,50,50,50,42,42,34,42,44,37,42,70,44,78,32,32,-5,0,-27,100,-10,53,51,61,61,146,91,52,48,50,19,19,26,28,28,28,61,46,60,77,76,76,66,74,65,62]} 1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nf3 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 d6 7. Nc3 {The starting position of the Leningrad Dutch. It is a big opening, and is mostly used if Black wants to play for a win.} c6 {The modern main line.} (7... Qe8 {[%csl Ge8] The old main line, the queen aims to go to f7.} 8. Re1 $1 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Ge2e4] Useful move, our idea is e4.} Qf7 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gf7c4] Black starts with attacking the c4 pawn.} (8... e5 {is as usual met with:} 9. e4 $1 {[%csl Ge1,Ge4,Re8] White is more ready to open the position than Black.} fxe4 10. dxe5 $1 {[%csl Re8][%cal Re4f3,Ge5f6] Intermezzo.} dxe5 11. Ng5 {[%csl Gg5] Very typical reaction.} Nc6 {The best, and after:} 12. Be3 h6 13. Ngxe4 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 $14 {[%csl Ge3,Ge4] White is positionally slightly better.}) 9. e4 $1 {[%csl Be4] We can sacrifice it.} fxe4 (9... Qxc4 $2 {Big mistake.} 10. exf5 Bxf5 11. Rxe7 $18 {[%csl Rb7,Rc7,Ge7][%cal Gf3h4] Black falls apart.}) 10. Nxe4 {This is simpler, since taking on c4 is not advisable.} (10. Ng5 {This leads to a forced line:} Qxc4 11. Ngxe4 Nxe4 12. Rxe4 $1 {We are following the game Mamedyarov-Grischuk, ½–½, FIDE GP Baku 2014.} Qf7 13. Rf4 Bf6 14. Bd5 $5 $146 {Improvement over the game.} (14. Nd5 {was played in the game, which is also a very reasonable try.}) 14... e6 15. Ne4 Qg7 16. Nxf6+ Rxf6 17. Rxf6 Qxf6 18. Bg2 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Gc1,Rc7,Rd6,Gg2][%cal Gc1e3] White has full compensation, and also some advantage, because Black still has to solve the problem of the weak structure and weak dark squares.}) 10... Nc6 $1 {The only playable move.} (10... Qxc4 $2 {Common mistake.} 11. Nxf6+ $1 exf6 (11... Bxf6 12. Bh6 $1 {Good tempo.} Rf7 13. Ne5 $3 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Re5c4,Re5f7] Simple tactic.} dxe5 14. dxe5 Bg7 15. Bd5 $18 {+2 for the engine.}) 12. Re7 $1 $16 {[%csl Rc7,Ge7][%cal Ge7g7,Ge7c7] The rook is too powerful and Black has concrete problems.} Rf7 $4 13. Nd2 $18 {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gg2d5,Rc4b5,Ga2a4] White wins.}) (10... Nxe4 $2 {also not advisable.} 11. Rxe4 $16 {White is just better.} Bf5 $2 {Common mistake.} 12. Ng5 $1 {The start of the refutation:} Qf6 13. Rh4 $1 {[%csl Rb7,Rh7][%cal Gg5h7,Gg2b7] Double attack.} h6 14. Bd5+ $1 {[%csl Gd5] Important intermezzo.} e6 15. Nxe6 Bxe6 16. Rf4 $1 $18 {[%csl Re6][%cal Rf6e7,Gf4e4] White wins. Gharamian-Nijboer, 1-0, Maastricht op 2010.}) 11. Neg5 $5 {Other moves are also okay, but this is the most principled.} Qxc4 12. b3 Qb5 {The best square.} (12... Qa6 $2 {The queen is very bad here.} 13. a4 $1 {[%csl Ra6] Good move.} h6 14. Ne6 Bxe6 15. Rxe6 $16 {White is positionally winning.}) 13. h3 $1 {[%csl Gh3][%cal Gh3g4] Important move, to guard the g4 square.} Nb4 {Best for the engine.} (13... h6 $2 {is met with:} 14. a4 $1 Qf5 15. Nh4 $1 $18 {[%csl Gh3][%cal Rf5g4] The point behind 13.h3.}) 14. Rxe7 h6 15. Ne6 Bxe6 16. Rxe6 {This position happened in 3 email games.} Qf5 17. Re2 $14 {For a human, Black's position is very unpleasant, engine agrees, although shows only around +0.50.}) (7... Nc6 $6 {Very common line, it has 8000 games, but I think that it's just not a good move.} 8. d5 $1 {[%csl Rc6,Gd5] We happily grab the tempo and space.} Ne5 {Main line.} (8... Na5 {Concrete try, used sometimes in short time controls.} 9. b3 $1 {[%csl Bb3] Only 100 games out of 2000, but it's the strongest. White is not afraid of anything.} c5 {[%csl Rf5,Gf7] Black goes for a theoretical position, but probably forgot that the pawn is on f5!} (9... Ne4 $6 {doesn't work.} 10. Nxe4 Bxa1 (10... fxe4 11. Nd4 $1 $16 {[%csl Gd4,Re4] Positionally winning for White.}) 11. Neg5 $1 {[%csl Gg5][%cal Gg5e6,Gc1d2] White has a winning compensation.} Bg7 12. e4 {More than +2 evaluation.} h6 13. Ne6 Bxe6 14. dxe6 $18 {[%cal Rf5e4,Gf3h4] I will not show any more lines, it will spoil you all the fun if this happens in your game!}) 10. Bd2 a6 11. e4 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ge4e5] This is the main difference, the structure is too exposed.} fxe4 12. Ng5 $16 {[%csl Re6] e6 square is very weak for Black.}) 9. Nxe5 dxe5 {This position happened in almost 3000 games.} 10. Qb3 $5 {[%csl Gb3,Rb7][%cal Gf1d1] I like this multi-purpose move, just develop the queen to target the weakness, and later on Rd1 is on the agenda.} (10. e4 $6 {Most common move, but it's a bit inaccurate.} f4 $1 $132 {[%csl Gf4] Black gets the desired counterplay.}) 10... e6 {The only critical try, to improve the structure, but still, it's bad.} (10... Kh8 {Another strange waiting move.} 11. Rd1 {[%csl Gd1] We can just finish development.} a6 12. Be3 Qe8 13. Rac1 $16 {[%cal Gc4c5] c5 next, White is better, with no need to calculate anything concrete.}) (10... h6 {Most common move, but quite strange.} 11. e4 $5 {[%csl Gb3,Rh6] Not necessary, but this critical move makes sense after Black wasted a tempo on h6.} (11. Rd1 $5 $16 {[%cal Gc4c5] is also a simple good move.}) 11... f4 12. gxf4 Nh5 {[%csl Gh5] Black can try to use this square, since the queen is not on d1.} 13. fxe5 Bxe5 14. Ne2 $1 {[%csl Be2] Defends everything.} g5 15. c5 Kh7 16. Bd2 $16 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gd2c3] Black doesn't have any targets to attack. White is better.}) 11. Rd1 $1 {[%csl Gd1,Rd8][%cal Gd1d8] Healthy move, bring the rook to an open file.} exd5 $2 {Concrete try, but fails tactically:} (11... Qe7 12. Nb5 $5 $16 {[%cal Ra7a6,Gd5d6] a6 is met with d6, just bad position for Black. Everything is holding by a thread.}) 12. Nxd5 $1 c6 13. Bg5 $3 {[%csl Bg5] Key move to remember.} cxd5 14. Bxd5+ Kh8 15. Bxb7 $18 {[%csl Ra8,Rd8] There are some old email games, but the line is refuted.}) (7... e6 $5 {[%cal Ge6e5,Yd4d5] Rare option, the idea is to be ready to meet d5 with e5 (no en passant).} 8. Re1 $1 {[%cal Ge2e4] White can prepare e4.} Ne4 {[%csl Ge4] Black's most logical response, to stop e4.} (8... Nc6 $6 {can be met with:} 9. d5 $1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Re6e5,Gd5c6] Attacking the knight, so Black doesn't have time for e5.} Ne5 10. Nd4 $16 {This was the game Giri-Nepo,½–½, Zagreb Blitz 2024. White is better, thanks to the light squares control.} Nxc4 $2 {Nepo took, but here White is just close to winning:} 11. Nxe6 Bxe6 12. dxe6 c6 13. e4 $1 $18 {[%csl Ge6] The game ended in a draw, but it was blitz after all.}) 9. Qc2 {The best.} Nxc3 {Main try.} (9... d5 {The Stonewall is not impressive here.} 10. Bf4 c6 11. Rad1 $14 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Gh2h4] White is long term better in many ways, it's not clear what the bishop on g7 is doing.}) 10. bxc3 $1 {[%csl Bc3][%cal Ge2e4] Important recapture, to have d4 well defended and follow up with e4.} (10. Qxc3 $6 {doesn't lead to anything.} e5 $1 {[%csl Be5] Black's common plan.} 11. dxe5 Nc6 $132 {[%csl Re5] Black has counterplay.}) 10... e5 11. e4 $1 {[%csl Ge4] Finally, White achieves it.} Nc6 12. exf5 $1 {was played in the game Gukesh-Sengupta, ½–½, FIDE World Cup Qual rapid 2021. It's the best move.} (12. dxe5 $5 {This also deserves attention, it's a simple way.} Nxe5 $1 $146 {[%csl Ge5] The most solid for Black, to trade the dangerous f3 knight off the board.} (12... dxe5 $6 {The only move that occured, but it's a positional mistake.} 13. exf5 $1 $146 {[%csl Re5] The Black structure is vulnerable.} gxf5 {Logical, to not have an isolated pawn.} (13... Bxf5 14. Qb3 {[%csl Re5] The doubled pawns are irelevant, White has a lot of activity and targets in return:} Rb8 15. Ba3 $16 {[%cal Ga1d1] Similar to the Gukesh game, White is better.}) 14. Bg5 $1 {[%csl Bg5] Important tempo.} Qd6 $1 {[%csl Bd6][%cal Gd6g6] The best square with idea Qg6.} (14... Qe8 $2 {Black's natural response fails tactically:} 15. Nxe5 $1 {[%csl Be5,Re8][%cal Ge1e8] Using the pin.} Nxe5 16. Bf4 $1 $18 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gf4e5] We take on e5 next and follow up with f4, and if Black tries to stop it with:} (16. f4 $4 {Be careful, not immediately!} Qh5 $1 $19 {[%csl Rg5] And White loses a piece.}) 16... Qe7 {[%cal Ge7c5] The most logical, to have Qc5+ somewhere.} 17. Bd5+ $1 {[%csl Gd5] Important tempo.} Kh8 18. Rxe5 $3 $18 {[%csl Ge5,Rh8][%cal Ga1e1] You have also this idea. White wins.}) 15. Nh4 $1 {[%csl Gg2,Rg6,Gh4][%cal Gh4g6] Good move, to control the square and open the bishop.} (15. Rad1 $6 {Logical, but it allows Qg6.} Qg6 $13 {Unclear battle.}) 15... e4 {Logical to close the diagonal, but not for long.} 16. Rad1 Qe5 (16... Qc5 17. g4 $1 $18 {[%csl Re4,Rf5,Gg2,Gg4][%cal Gg2e4,Rf5g4,Rd1d5] Typical idea, to open up everything.}) 17. g4 $1 $16 {[%cal Rf5g4,Gd1d5] To dismantle the structure, and White has a big advantage.}) 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. exf5 Bxf5 {[%csl Rb7,Gg2][%cal Gg2b7] Black's position looks fine visually, but the g2 bishop is a monster now:} 15. Qb3 $5 {[%csl Gb3] Difficult to say which square is the best.} Qf6 $1 {[%csl Rc3,Rf2,Bf6][%cal Ge5c3,Gf6f2] The only move, but easy to find, Black targets two pawns with one move.} 16. Re3 $1 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Ge3c3] The rook does a very good job on e3, and Black can't make use of the weak f2 pawn.} g5 $1 {[%csl Bg5][%cal Rf2f4] Black must stop f4.} (16... Bg4 $6 17. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Rb7,Re5][%cal Gf2f4,Gg2b7] f4 and Bxb7 are 2 difficult threats to deal with.}) 17. c5+ {We are quite deep, but the position is playable:} Be6 18. Qb2 h6 19. Qe2 Rae8 20. cxd6 cxd6 21. Ba3 $14 {White is slightly better, but it is quite unlikely that this position will ever happen.}) 12... Bxf5 (12... gxf5 {can be met with:} 13. Bg5 {[%csl Gg5] Good tempo.} Bf6 {The best.} (13... Qe8 $2 14. dxe5 $18 {[%cal Rd6e5,Gf3e5] And you can see the continuation in the 12.dxe5 line.}) 14. Bh6 $16 {[%cal Rf8f7,Gh2h4] White is positionally better.}) 13. Qb3 exd4 $1 $146 {This novelty is worth trying for Black.} (13... Rb8 $6 {The only move that has been played, and also Sengupta's choice, but White's better in many ways:} 14. c5+ $5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gc5d6] Gukesh's move is very logical, to undouble the pawns.} Kh8 15. cxd6 cxd6 16. dxe5 {Good capture, Black has concrete problems.} dxe5 17. Ba3 $16 {[%csl Ga3,Rf7][%cal Ga1d1,Yf3g5] White was much better in the game, although it ended in a draw.}) 14. Bg5 $1 {[%csl Bg5] Good tempo against the queen.} Qd7 15. Nxd4 {[%csl Gb3,Gg2] White unleashes the activity.} Nxd4 16. cxd4 Rae8 $1 {[%csl Ge8] Black should control the entry square for the rook.} (16... Bxd4 $2 {too greedy.} 17. Re7 $1 {[%csl Be7] The rook enters with devastating effect.} Bxa1 {The best try.} 18. Rxd7 Bxd7 19. c5+ $1 $18 {[%csl Rb7,Rd6,Rg8][%cal Gc5d6,Gb3b7] Despite material equality, White is winning thanks to the various threats.}) 17. Qxb7 c5 $3 {[%csl Bc5] This is Black's idea, although the defensive task is not easy at all:} 18. Qd5+ Kh8 19. dxc5 $1 {We can sacrifice the exchange.} Bxa1 20. Rxa1 dxc5 21. Qxc5 $14 {Material is equal, and the dark squares are extremely weak, that's why it's unlikely that somebody will enter this line with Black. However, the engine shows brilliant defensive skills:} Qg7 $1 {[%csl Bg7][%cal Gg7f8] Important tempo against a1.} 22. Rc1 Be4 $1 {[%csl Ge4,Gf8,Bg7][%cal Rg2e4,Ge8e4] This is Black's idea, f8 is defended.} 23. Be3 $1 {[%csl Ra7,Rg7][%cal Ge3d4,Gc5a7] Double attack.} Rc8 $1 {Last accurate move, and now the position simplifies:} 24. Qxa7 Qxa7 25. Bxa7 Bxg2 26. Kxg2 Rc6 $1 $44 {[%csl Gc6] Probably Black will hold this endgame. This line is unlikely to happen, but you have also an alternative.}) 8. Qb3 $5 {[%csl Gb3] Once again, the queen development to b3 is the best.} Na6 (8... Kh8 {Prophylactic move.} 9. Re1 $1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ge2e4] We go for our typical plan.} Ne4 {We can use the same idea as we have seen.} (9... Na6 {is met with:} 10. e4 {White has a huge advantage, for example:} fxe4 11. Nxe4 Nxe4 12. Rxe4 Bf5 13. Rh4 $1 $16 {[%csl Rb7,Rh8][%cal Gf3g5] White has a lot of threats.}) 10. Qc2 $1 {[%csl Re4] To force Black to capture.} Nxc3 11. bxc3 $1 {[%csl Bc3] Standard way, and White is better after providing e4:} e5 12. dxe5 (12. e4 $16 {Very good move as well.}) 12... dxe5 13. Ba3 {We can follow the game Eljanov-Nakamura, 1-0, Titled Tuesday 2024.} Re8 14. Rad1 {Before e4, White gained some tempi on the queen:} Qf6 15. Rd6 Qf7 16. Ng5 $1 $16 {[%cal Ge2e4] followed by e4 was even more straight-forward.} (16. e4 {was played in the game, also good enough.})) (8... Qb6 $6 {is met with:} 9. Qc2 $16 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Rd8e8,Re7e5,Rb6c7,Gb2b4,Gc4c5] The queen is misplaced on b6, because it doesn't support the e5 break.}) 9. Bf4 $5 {This is an useful developing move, against e5.} (9. Re1 {can be met with:} Qb6 $1 {Strong move, played in Supi-Cheparinov, ½–½, Olympiad 2018.} 10. Qc2 Qc7 $132 {[%csl Ga6][%cal Rb2b4,Rc4c5] The knight on a6 is very well placed against c5 and b4 ideas.}) 9... h6 {Most common move.} (9... Nh5 {is met with:} 10. c5+ $1 {[%csl Gb3,Rg8] Important check.} Kh8 11. cxd6 exd6 {was tried in Bellahcene-Soham,½–½, Baden-Baden Swiss 2021.} (11... Nxf4 {We have another intermezzo:} 12. dxe7 $1 {[%csl Rd8,Ge7,Rf8][%cal Ge7d8,Ge7f8]} Nxe2+ 13. Nxe2 Qxe7 14. Nf4 $16 {Big positional advantage. Perez Gormaz-Caspi, ½–½, Belgrade op 2021.}) 12. Bg5 Qe8 13. d5 $5 $14 {[%csl Gd5] Positional advantage, maybe slight improvement over the game.}) (9... Qe8 {is also met with:} 10. c5+ $1 {[%csl Gc5,Rd6] Forcing d5.} d5 11. Rfe1 $16 {Better with any move.}) (9... c5 $5 {[%csl Gc5] Engine tries to go for some kind of Benoni Hybrid, but it's very rare.} 10. d5 Nc7 11. Rfe1 $146 {[%cal Ge2e4] Standard plan to prepare e4.} e5 12. dxe6 Nxe6 13. Bg5 $5 {[%csl Gd5,Gg5][%cal Gg5f6,Gc3d5] Positional decision, to control the d5 square.} Nxg5 14. Nxg5 h6 15. Nh3 $1 {[%cal Gh3f4] The knight goes to the dream d5 square.} g5 16. f4 $1 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Gd5,Rd6,Bf4][%cal Ga1d1] White has a safe and long term positional advantage.}) 10. Rad1 Qe8 {is met with:} 11. c5+ $1 {[%csl Gb3,Bc5,Rd6,Gf4,Rg8][%cal Gb3g8,Gf4d6] The point of having a bishop on f4.} d5 12. Rfe1 {This position doesn't require much knowledge, just positionally better for White:} Nd7 {[%csl Gd7][%cal Ge7e5] Black tries to justify it concretely, but it runs into:} (12... Kh7 $146 {Sample line:} 13. Be5 Nb8 14. e3 Nbd7 15. Qc2 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 $16 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gb2b4] Black has no counterplay.}) 13. e4 $3 {[%csl Gb3,Be4,Rg8] Important move, using the pin.} fxe4 14. Nxe4 Qf7 {And you would expect some knight jumps and sacrifices, but no, White has a fantastic move:} 15. Bf1 $3 {[%csl Gf1][%cal Gf1c4,Rd5e4] Key prophylactic move.} Nc7 $1 {The best move, but there are only 4 email games here.} 16. Bxc7 Qxf3 17. Re3 $1 Qf7 18. f4 $14 {[%cal Gf2f3] or the safer move f3, White has a positional advantage.} *

