{[%evp 0,24,19,25,74,70,69,56,63,64,53,36,60,56,51,58,68,36,41,41,41,18,31,8,47,44,42]} 1. d4 f5 {[%csl Bf5] In the following three Chapters we will study the Dutch Defense.} 2. g3 {[%csl Bg3] Most solid move order.} Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 (3... g6 {leads to the Leningrad variation.}) (3... d6 {also leads to the Leningrad variation.}) 4. Nf3 Be7 (4... d5 {leads to the Stonewall.}) 5. O-O O-O 6. c4 {[%csl Bc4] Please note that I prefer to play c4 only now. If White plays c4 on some earlier move, Black might have Bb4+ extra options.} d6 7. Nc3 {This is the starting position of the "Classical Dutch", an opening with a very rich history and more than 10K games.} Ne4 {[%csl Be4] The most direct and important move.} (7... Qe8 {Used to be Black's mainline, but here White can grab queenside space by playing} 8. b4 $1 {[%csl Cb4] This is not White's most common move, but it's the first engine's choice.} Qh5 {logical continuation.} (8... a5 9. b5 $1 {[%csl Bb5] and White has a big positional advantage. The most common continuation here is} Nbd7 10. a4 e5 {but now White has a winning position after} 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 13. Qxd5+ Qf7 14. Ng5 $1 Bxg5 15. Bxg5 $18 {[%csl Cg2,Cg5] Two bishops and huge space advantage. According to my engine, the evaluation is +2,50.}) (8... Ne4 $2 {loses material:} 9. Nxe4 fxe4 10. Nd2 d5 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Qb3 $18 {[%csl Rd5,Re4,Rg8][%cal Gb3d5,Gd2e4] d5 or e4 will fall.}) 9. a4 Ne4 10. Qc2 Nxc3 11. Qxc3 {[%cal Gc4c5] White is ready to expand on the queenside and Black has zero counterplay, for example:} Nd7 12. b5 Nf6 13. Ba3 Ne4 14. Qc2 $16 {[%cal Gc4c5,Ge2e3,Gf3d2] c5 next, or just e3 followed by Nd2.}) (7... a5 {[%cal Rb2b4,Gd8e8] Black stops b4 and is ready to continue now with Qe8.} 8. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Cf4] very deep move shown by the engine.} Qe8 {this was Black's idea, right?} (8... Ne4 9. Qc2 Nxc3 10. bxc3 $16 {[%csl Ra5][%cal Rb8c6,Rc6a5,Ge2e4] White is ready to push e4. Compared to the 7...Ne4 variation, here Black doesn't have the Nc6-Na5 plan.}) 9. Re1 {[%csl Ge1][%cal Ge2e4] White is ready to push e4.} Ne4 {typical move to stop e4.} (9... Qh5 10. e4 $16) 10. Nxe4 fxe4 11. Nd2 {[%csl Re4]} d5 12. Bxc7 $1 $16 {[%csl Bc7] This is the idea of 8.Bf4!}) 8. Nxe4 $1 {[%csl Be4] This is the best way to fight for the advantage.} (8. Qc2 {is White's most common continuation, but after} Nxc3 9. Qxc3 (9. bxc3 $5 {could be more interesting, but also here Black will be fine after} Nc6 $1 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gc6a5] Nc6 is useful for e5, but also for Na5, which is a very good square against White's structure.} 10. d5 (10. e4 e5 $1 $11) 10... Na5 {[%csl Ba5]} 11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. Nd4 Bxc4 13. Nxf5 {Black has a lot of normal moves here. Of course, the position is playable, but very difficult to think that this is a safe advantage for White (engine's evaluation is +0,25).}) 9... a5 $1 {[%cal Rb2b4] strong positional move against b4.} 10. b3 Nc6 11. Bb2 Bf6 $132 {[%cal Gd8e8,Ge6e5] Black can continue with Qe8-e5, and has a very playable position.}) 8... fxe4 9. Ne1 $5 {[%csl Ce1] This is my main recommendation. You can also try 9.Nd2, of course, but it's more concrete and unclear.} (9. Nd2 {is White's most common continuation.} d5 10. f3 Nc6 $1 {[%csl Gc6,Rd4][%cal Gc6d4] strong move that puts immediate pressure on d4.} (10... exf3 $6 11. Nxf3 Nc6 12. Be3 $16 {[%cal Gd1d3] Qd3 next and it's just positionally better for White.}) 11. fxe4 (11. e3 {could be a solid line, but Black is fine here with} exf3 12. Nxf3 b6 13. Bd2 Bb7 $132) 11... Rxf1+ {and now White has a lot of possible recaptures.} 12. Kxf1 $1 {[%csl Cf1][%cal Gd2f3] This is in my opinion, White's best chance. We take with the king because we want our knight on f3.} (12. Qxf1 $6 Nxd4 $15) (12. Nxf1 {most natural and common move, but here it's immediately equal and unclear.} dxc4 $1 13. Be3 Bd7 $13 {[%cal Gb7b5] b5 next, it's an interesting but very unclear position.}) 12... dxc4 (12... Nxd4 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Nb3 $1 $16) 13. Nf3 {[%csl Rd4,Bf3] Now d4 is well-defended.} b5 14. Be3 {Also here it's unclear, but White has good chances for an advantage, for example:} Rb8 (14... Qe8 15. d5 $1 Nb4 16. a3 Na6 17. b3 $36) 15. Kg1 $5 {[%csl Bg1] Useful move.} Qe8 (15... Qd6 16. Kh1 $14 {[%csl Bh1]}) 16. d5 exd5 17. Qxd5+ Kh8 18. Ng5 $36) 9... d5 10. Be3 {[%csl Ce3] First, I'd like to consolidate my position, and only later will I think about f2-f3.} Nc6 (10... Nd7 11. Qc2 {[%csl Bc2,Yd7] when Black's knight is not on c6, we can consider Qc2.} Nf6 (11... Bg5 {Engine's recommendation, but White is also slightly better after} 12. Qd2 Bxe3 13. Qxe3 Nf6 14. f3 $14) 12. Rd1 $14 {[%csl Bc2,Bd1,Be3][%cal Gf2f3] now that all the pieces are well-placed, I am ready for f3.}) 11. Rc1 {[%csl Bc1,Rc6] But Rc1 is a very good move against Black's Nc6.} (11. Qc2 {now I don't like Qc2 because Black will have Nb4 ideas.} a5 12. Rd1 Nb4 13. Qb1 a4 $13) 11... a5 $1 $146 {[%csl Ca5] Engine's recommendation and it's a novelty. But it's not a surprising move for me, because we have already seen on many occasions that a7-a5 is a good move for Black.} (11... Bd7 12. f3 $14) (11... Na5 12. b3 $14 {[%csl Ra5]}) (11... Bf6 {Black's most common move, but here White is just better after} 12. f3 $1 exf3 (12... dxc4 13. Rxc4 e5 14. d5 $1 exf3 15. Nxf3 Ne7 16. Bc5 $16) 13. Nxf3 $16 {[%cal Gd1d3] Qd3 next.}) 12. f3 e5 $1 {This is probably Black's best line, and here we have two directions:} 13. cxd5 (13. fxe4 Rxf1+ 14. Kxf1 dxe4 $1 (14... exd4 $6 15. exd5 dxe3 16. dxc6 bxc6 17. Qxd8+ Bxd8 18. Bxc6 $14 {Black doesn't have full compensation for the pawn.}) 15. d5 {and now there is a semi-forced line:} Qf8+ 16. Kg1 Nd4 17. Bxe4 Bf5 18. Bxd4 Bxe4 19. Bxe5 Qf5 20. Bd4 Rf8 21. Nf3 h5 $1 $44 {where Black has full compensation.}) 13... Qxd5 14. fxe4 Rxf1+ 15. Bxf1 Qxe4 16. Qb3+ Kh8 17. Bg2 {and now Black's position is not so bad only because of} a4 $1 {[%csl Ba4]} (17... Qf5 $6 {would be a mistake.} 18. Nf3 a4 19. Qc3 $16) 18. Bxe4 (18. Qc3 exd4 $1 $13 {[%csl Cc3][%cal Gd4c3]}) 18... axb3 19. axb3 exd4 20. Bf4 {for a human eye this looks better for White, but the engine finds the strong} Bg4 $1 $11 {[%csl Bg4] and claims that the endgame is equal.} *

