{[%evp 0,43,28,28,69,44,44,48,48,49,44,40,89,85,69,50,55,39,43,22,52,41,45,9,36,6,43,37,39,13,58,51,55,15,79,52,82,75,89,72,78,80,80,79,63,64]} 1. d4 f5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 4. Nf3 d5 5. c4 c6 {The Stonewall Dutch. It is a common opening, that's why I wanted to recommend something practical, that can be studied once and remembered for a long time. This way, whenever it happens, it won't catch you by surprise.} 6. Nc3 {[%csl Ge1] The key point is that White will delay castling for some time.} Bd6 {Most common way to develop.} (6... Be7 7. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Gf4] The best square for the bishop.} O-O 8. Qc2 $5 {[%csl Gc2][%cal Ga1d1] For the moment, we make useful development moves.} (8. O-O $6 {We shouldn't hurry with this move, because Black can use his kingside control:} Ne4 9. Qc2 g5 $5 $13 {[%csl Bg5] White maybe has some advantage here as well, but there is no need to study this.}) 8... Ne4 {Most logical try.} (8... dxc4 $146 {Engine tries to open up the position, but of course it is a difficult strategy for a human.} 9. O-O Nd5 10. Bd2 b5 11. b3 $1 {[%csl Bb3] Typical way to put pressure.} cxb3 12. Qxb3 $14 {[%csl Re6,Rf5][%cal Ge2e4] We have Catalan style compensation, and White is for sure better thanks to the weakening move f5.}) 9. Rd1 g5 10. Bc1 $1 {[%csl Bc1,Gd1] This is the point, the bishop on c1 cannot be targeted, and also with the king on e1, there is no attack going on.} Nd7 11. h4 {[%csl Rg5,Gh4] Good move, to clarify the situation.} g4 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nxc3 14. Qxc3 Bd7 {When everything is locked up this way, it's time to castle.} 15. O-O $16 {[%csl Gc1,Gg2] White has a positional advantage thanks to the better pawn structure.}) 7. Bf4 $1 {[%csl Gf4] We must fight for the e5 square, and also develop the bishop before locking it with e3.} Bxf4 $1 {The only critical move, otherwise, 8.e3 and White is just much better.} (7... O-O {is met with:} 8. e3 $1 {[%csl Be3,Re6][%cal Be3f4,Ge1e6] Important move, because we want to capture on f4 with the e-pawn if possible, this way we can target the e6 pawn.} Ne4 (8... Bxf4 9. exf4 $1 $16 {[%csl Re6,Gf2,Gf4,Gg3,Gh2] This is a much better structure compared to if White is forced to take with the g-pawn.}) 9. h4 $1 {[%csl Cf4,Bh4][%cal Rg7g5] We can secure the bishop, and not allow Black to expand with g5.} Qe7 10. Rc1 Nd7 11. O-O {We can finish development, and now the maneuvering begins.} b6 {is met with:} 12. cxd5 $1 {[%csl Yb6,Rc6][%cal Re6d5] Standard Stonewall reaction, whenever you see b6 on the board, this move deserves consideration, since Black's desired recapture (exd5) leaves the c6 pawn weak.} cxd5 13. Bxd6 Nxd6 (13... Qxd6 14. Nb5 $1 $16 {[%csl Rc7] A piece is landing on c7 with devastating effects.}) 14. Qb3 {[%cal Gb3a3] Cute maneuver.} Bb7 15. Qa3 Rfe8 16. Ne2 $16 {[%cal Ge2f4,Gc1c2,Gf1c1] Black can play it, but trust me, you won't see a smile on your opponent's face.}) 8. gxf4 O-O {The main line by far.} (8... dxc4 $5 {For the engine this is the strongest option, but once again, it's unlikely that it will happen.} 9. Ne5 Nbd7 10. Nxc4 $14 {[%cal Ge2e3] +0.40, but the position is new, and Black still has huge positional problems to deal with.}) 9. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Ge1] This is my recommendation, there are only 10 games, and I am the strongest player with White who played it. The concept is really simple: we will only castle when it's useful for us.} (9. O-O $6 {There is no need to castle.}) 9... Nbd7 (9... Qe7 {This is how my opponent Motuz played.} 10. e3 Nbd7 11. Ne5 {I placed a knight on e5, just to harrass Black's development.} (11. cxd5 $5 {You can consider taking on d5 without waiting for b6 as well.} exd5 {[%csl Gb7,Gc6,Gd5] Black's natural recapture.} 12. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] This is a strong move, to grab as much space as possible.} Ne4 13. h5 Ndf6 14. h6 {You can include this move or not, depending on taste.} g6 15. Ne5 $14 {White has great long term chances.}) 11... Kh8 12. h4 $5 {[%csl Gh4][%cal Gh4h5] This is in general an useful move.} a5 13. cxd5 $5 {[%csl Ra5] a5 is a weakening of the structure, so I decided to take on d5.} exd5 14. a3 {The move I chose.} (14. Qa3 $5 {is also very interesting, if you like technical tasks:} Qxa3 15. bxa3 $16 {+1 evaluation.}) 14... Nxe5 15. fxe5 Ne8 16. f4 b5 {Position is borderline hopeless for Black, but I really enjoyed the plan that I chose:} 17. Nd1 $1 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Gd1f2,Gf2d3] The knight is rerouted to the dream square.} Ba6 18. Rc1 Qd7 19. Bf1 {[%csl Gc1,Gd1,Ge1,Gf1,Gh1] All the pieces are on the home rank, but White is in fact positionally winning.} Nc7 20. Qc2 Bb7 21. Nf2 Ne6 22. Nd3 $18 {[%cal Gd3c5] Later on I jumped to c5 as well, and overall it was a pretty simple game, without mistakes. Basso-Motuz, 1-0, 2020.}) 10. e3 {[%csl Ce3] One more useful move.} b6 {Once tried by Magnus Carlsen.} 11. Rc1 (11. cxd5 $5 $146 {[%csl Rc6,Gd5][%cal Re6d5] Starting with cxd5 is also very healthy, since exd5 is out of the question for Black.}) 11... Bb7 12. cxd5 cxd5 (12... exd5 13. h4 $16 {[%csl Rb6,Rc6,Rd5,Ge5,Rf5][%cal Gh4h5,Gf3e5] The structure is worse for Black with a pawn on f7 as well, here with the pawn on f5 it is just unplayable, e5 square is ours forever.}) 13. O-O {[%csl Gf1,Gg1] Now when White achieved some positional trumps, it's a good time to bring the other rook into the game as well.} Ne4 14. Nb5 $1 {[%csl Gb5] The knight is great.} Ba6 15. Rfe1 {[%cal Gb5c7] Nc7 is a threat.} Bxb5 16. Qxb5 Rc8 {It looks kind of playable for Black, but in reality, it is very unpleasant:} 17. Qa4 $1 {[%csl Ra7] a7 is a target.} Rf7 $1 {[%csl Bf7] This is engine's prophylactic move, but difficult to understand the idea:} (17... Rc7 $6 {is almost an automatic move, but it runs into:} 18. Rc6 $1 $16 {[%csl Re6,Rf5,Cf7] White is better.}) 18. Rxc8 Qxc8 19. Qxa7 h6 $1 {[%csl Gf7][%cal Gg7g5,Gf7g7] This is Black's point.} 20. Qa4 g5 21. Ne5 $16 {However it is still around +0.60/70, so White should be more than happy to play with a pawn up.} *

